<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, March 31, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Father Said Angry for Delay
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A senior Cuban official Friday said Elian Gonzalez's father is
''frustrated'' and ''angry'' by the pace of efforts to reclaim his 6-year-old
son, two and a half months after the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
said he should be reunited with him. The INS has twice moved back deadlines to
revoke the relative's temporary custody pending more negotiations. In Miami,
Elian's relatives Friday said they would let Gonzalez visit him at their Little
Havana home, but that they are no longer willing to give Elian to his father.
They said they would not resist if the government tried to take Elian from their
house.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Volcano Erupts Twice
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- A volcano in northern Japan erupted twice on Saturday, a
day after it roared to life and sent a spectacular plume of molten rock and ash
billowing two miles above the crater and rolling down the snow-quilted slopes.
Mount Usu ejected smoke and brightened the sky before dawn Saturday, and erupted
again a few hours later. Experts said the blasts appeared to be less powerful
than Friday's. On Friday, ash dusted silent, evacuated villages near the volcano
following its first eruption in 22 years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mich. Boy Denies Shooting Classmate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- With little more than his eyes and nose visible over the
witness stand, a 6-year-old boy Friday denied that he shot classmate Kayla
Rolland to death and blamed another first-grader. The boy testified at a
preliminary hearing for Jamelle James, 19, who is accused of carelessly storing
the semiautomatic handgun that the 6-year-old allegedly found and used to kill
Kayla on Feb. 29. James is charged with involuntary manslaughter; the 6-year-old
isn't charged.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tensions Rise Over Zimbabwe Farms
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Civic groups and opposition parties were warned by
police Friday to call off a scheduled peace march as tensions worsened here over
black war veterans' occupation of white-owned farmland. The unrest began in
February, when veterans armed with spears, axes, clubs and guns smashed their
way into white farmers' homesteads and seized their spreads. President Robert
Mugabe has called the occupation a justifiable political protest against the
descendants of white settlers who ruled here during the colonial era. Police
have refused to evict the squatters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Farmers Shy Away From Biotech Crops
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farmers are turning away from genetically engineered
crops, especially a biotech corn that's toxic to insects, amid consumer
resistance that started overseas and is now being felt in the United States.
Plantings of the gene-altered corn are projected to drop 24 percent this year,
according to findings of an Agriculture Department survey released Friday. The
biotech corn became especially controversial last year after a Cornell
University study suggested it could be killing Monarch butterflies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Income, Spending Both Rose in Feb.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- American consumers, the driving force behind the
supercharged economy, spent with abandon in February at a pace more than double
their income growth. It dragged the personal savings rate to a record low.
Economists said Friday's report shows that the Federal Reserve has not finished
raising interest rates to slow the economy and keep inflation from becoming a
problem.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Man Stowed Away Aboard Flight
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A man hid in the cargo hold of a Northwest Airlines flight
Friday and traveled more than 2,000 miles to Memphis, Tenn., where he fled into
the terminal and disappeared. The stowaway settled into the heated and
pressurized front section of the cargo hold, where pets are kept, as Flight 946
left Seattle on Friday morning, KIRO-TV reported. On arrival in Memphis, he
asked baggage handlers for a ride to the terminal, KIRO reported. When the
handlers challenged him, he fled.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 58.33, Nasdaq Up 114.94
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks edged back from the brink Friday, and the
Nasdaq was up 114.94 at 4,572.83, even though it finished the week 9.4 percent
below its March 10 record high close. The Dow industrials closed down 58.33 at
10,921.92. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led decliners
2,017-1,073.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Connecticut Beats Penn State 89-67
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- With the biggest stars from UConn's glorious past in the
stands, the Huskies ended Penn State's run of upsets Friday night with an 89-67
victory over the Lady Lions in the NCAA Final Four women's basketball matchup.
UConn (35-1) gets a chance to repeat its glorious title run of 1995 in a rematch
Sunday night with the Lady Vols, who beat Rutgers 64-54. Sue Bird led the
Huskies with 19 points, hitting five crucial 3-pointers and running Penn State
(30-5) ragged all night.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
