<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Septic system, not cow manure, may have caused outbreak  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The E. coli outbreak at a county fair last
summer could have been caused by a septic system, not cow manure
seeping in to wellwater, a state Health Department study said.
</P>
<P>
   But neither source of the outbreak could be ruled out, health
officials concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Samples from Well 6 at the Washington County Fairgrounds in
Greenwich had tested positive for O157:H7, the strain of E. coli
that sickened hundreds and claimed the life of two people -- a
3-year-old girl and a 79-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report released Friday, investigators found
that water flowed between the septic system of a dormitory and Well
6, which supplied unchlorinated water to the southwestern parts of
the fairgrounds. Strains of the toxic bacteria were found in the
dormitory of the septic system, about 36 feet from the well.
</P>
<P>
   No water-flow connection was established between the manure
storage area and the contaminated well. But officials added ''it
may never been known if manure-contaminated water percolated from
the manure storage area to Well 6'' because manure was removed
daily and the exact environmental condition at the fair could not
be reproduced.
</P>
<P>
   A long period of drought followed by heavy rain during the fair
had led officials to suspect that runoff from the manure led to
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   The manure storage area was located about 80 feet from the well.
No E. coli O157:H7 strain was isolated from manure samples from the
Youth Cattle Barn, 50 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   The single-story dormitory building was operated by Cornell
Cooperative Extension and housed 80 children and their chaperones
during the fair. Twenty Boy Scouts camped next to the building and
also used dormitory facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The source of E. coli found in the septic system could not be
determined, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   During the outbreak, the Health Department had reported that
suspected E. coli infection cases were expected to rise above
1,000. But the department's final count in the study had the number
at 781. Of those, 127 cases were confirmed. Seventy-one people were
hospitalized, 14 of them developing hemolytic uremic syndrome, a
severe complication that could lead to kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of those sickened by possible E. coli
contamination attended the fair, 35 miles north of Albany, during
its last weekend on Aug. 28-29 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Following the outbreak, state Health Commissioner Dr. Antonia
Novello issued emergency orders prohibiting the use of untreated
water at seven agricultural fairgrounds: Chenango County
Agriculture Society; Genesee County Agricultural Society, Inc.;
Madison County Agricultural Society; Washington County Fair, Inc.;
Wyoming County Fair Association, Inc.; Cooperative Extension
Association of Orleans County; and Tioga County Fair have been told
to assess their water supply systems and disinfect their water
through chlorination or other means.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will take whatever steps are necessary to ensure that a
tragedy of this nature never happens again, and that New Yorkers
can count on a clean, safe water supply,'' Novello said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
