<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More blacks betting on Quick Draw and facing gambling problems  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A state senator is calling on the state
Lottery Division to stop offering Quick Draw after a new study
indicated more poor blacks and Hispanics are playing the game and
being classified as problem gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This report appears to confirm our worst fears,'' Queens
Republican Frank Padavan said. ''As we suspected when first
proposed -- and we called it 'video crack' -- Quick Draw produces
greater numbers of problem gamblers than other gambling
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The study released Friday also showed that more weekly players
of the rapid-fire game offered in bars, restaurants, bowling alleys
and other gathering places are problem or pathological gamblers
compared with those who play other Lottery games each week, 11.5
percent vs. 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the study showed there was no significant increase in
the percentage of problem or pathological gamblers playing Quick
Draw weekly between 1996 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited study was prepared for the state Office of
Mental Health by Rachel Volberg of Northampton, Mass., a veteran
researcher of gambling problems. It was a study OMH took charge of
after critics derided a 1999 attempt by the state Lottery Division
to evaluate the compulsive gambling threat of Quick Draw. The
critics pointed out that the study was conducted by a consulting
firm selected by the division's ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Volberg study shows that the Lottery Division has been
''targeting low-income minority neighborhoods in the hope of
hooking problem gamblers and that it has been succeeding,'' Padavan
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Volberg said the increase in problem or compulsive gambling
among minorities playing Quick Draw weekly was of ''particular
concern.'' She found that about 25 percent of the blacks and 15
percent of the Hispanics studied in 1999 could be classified as
problem or compulsive gamblers, compared with 8 percent of the
whites playing Quick Draw weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ''It concluded what we already knew,'' said Laura Letson, head
of the New York Council for Problem Gambling. ''Quick Draw is not a
problem for a majority, however there is still a percentage of the
population experiencing difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the state runs the game, it also needs to set aside
funding for helping problem gamblers at a greater level than is
presently spent, she added. Letson also called for lengthier study
of Quick Draw.
</P>
<P>
   Padavan also criticized OMH for making the report public on a
Friday afternoon -- traditionally state government's favorite time
for releasing information that agencies want buried. In addition,
Friday was the first day since Sunday that the state Legislature
did not meet in Albany, Padavan pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at the Lottery Division said officials there
hadn't seen the report and she declined to comment on it.
Spokeswoman Sue Miller also would not comment on Padavan's charges
that the Lottery Division is targeting poor and minority players
with the Quick Draw game or that the state should discontinue
offering it.
</P>
<P>
   Also among the study's findings were:
</P>
<P>
   --Proportionately fewer whites are playing Quick Draw each week
than in 1996, down from about 90 percent to 68 percent in 1999,
while the proportions of blacks (from 2 percent in 1996 to 16
percent in 1999) and Hispanics (6 percent in 1996 to nearly 14
percent in 1999) were significantly higher.
</P>
<P>
   --Weekly players earning $25,000 or less a year increased from 26
percent in 1996 to more than 29 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   --There were significantly more non-white females playing Quick
Draw each week in 1999 -- 29 percent of all female players -- than
the 3.6 percent non-white females who were playing the game in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   --A review of 1999 client records at three of the six problem
gambling treatment centers in the state indicated that Quick Draw
''does play a role as a trigger for relapse for some problem
gamblers.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Letson, head of the New York Council for Problem Gambling
was on an airplane Friday when the report was released and not
available for comment, her office said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
