<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Pataki leads rivals for possible governor's race  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki continues to lead two
potential Democratic rivals for the 2002 governor's race, a
statewide poll has reported.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee Miringoff, head of Marist College's Institute for Public
Opinion, said Friday the new poll ''points to a competitive
re-election campaign'' for Pataki if he decides to seek a third
term.
</P>
<P>
   The Marist poll had Pataki at 50 percent and federal Housing
Secretary Andrew Cuomo at 40 percent in one possible matchup. It
had Pataki leading state Comptroller H. Carl McCall, 52 percent to
33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of McCall have said the comptroller, the only black
thus far elected to statewide office in New York, has told them
privately that he will run for governor. Publicly, McCall has said
he will announce his plans after this November's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, the son of former Gov. Mario Cuomo, who Pataki drove from
office in 1994, has said he is considering the race.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Pataki, who said during his 1994 campaign for
governor that he would serve only two terms if elected, has since
said he is considering running for a third term in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's lead over the younger Cuomo is statistically unchanged
from a September poll from Marist. McCall has closed the gap
against Pataki a bit. In September, Pataki led McCall, 54 percent
to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Marist poll did not ask Democrats who they would vote for in
a possible primary between Cuomo and McCall.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting finding in the poll was that Sen. Charles
Schumer's approval rating has slipped to 39 percent, down from 44
percent in September. But Miringoff noted that Schumer's
disapproval rating has also fallen, from 39 percent in September to
34 percent in the new poll.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, said the pollster, is the victim of being pushed out of
the limelight in New York because of the Senate race between
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''It reflects what happens when Hillary and Rudy decide to do
their thing in your state,'' Miringoff said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's job approval rating is at 51 percent in the
latest poll, statistically unchanged from September's poll, but
down from the 61 percent approval rating the governor enjoyed one
year ago in the Marist poll.
</P>
<P>
   One good sign for Pataki, according to Miringoff, is that 60
percent of voters surveyed feel the state is headed in the right
direction while only 29 percent say it is headed in the wrong
direction. A year ago, 64 percent of voters felt New York was
headed in the right direction while 26 percent felt it was going
the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear the people of New York support the governor's
policies and his leadership,'' Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon
said.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll by the Poughkeepsie-based pollsters of 561
registered voters was conducted Monday and Tuesday and has a margin
of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
