<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrests at Black College Reunion  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE SCHNEIDER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Police made more than 60 arrests,
most for minor infractions such as drug possession or disorderly
conduct, as thousands of young men and women descended on this
beach community for Black College Reunion this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''The arrests that have been made have been for relatively minor
things,'' Volusia County Sheriff Bob Vogel said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One person was cut with a knife and required stitches, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal officials and local NAACP leaders were
monitoring local businesses for any signs of discrimination against
the guests.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the scrutiny was the Adam's Mark, the area's
largest hotel, which was accused of discriminating against black
guests during last year's reunion. The company recently settled for
$8 million two lawsuits brought by the U.S. Justice Department and
five former guests and promised to revise its policies.
</P>
<P>
   Most noticeably, black hotel guests this year weren't required
to wear orange wristbands as they were last year. Guests, however,
were required to pay in advance in full for their rooms and were
required to leave a $50 deposit to use the telephone and snack bar
in their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Mark officials said reunion visitors were being treated
the same as guests during other special events, such as Bike Week
and spring break.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is nothing that we are doing at this hotel that is out
of the ordinary or that is in any sense racially motivated,'' said
Fred S. Kummer III, Adam's Mark' vice president of corporate
affairs. Kummer and his father, CEO and president Fred Kummer, flew
down from the company's St. Louis headquarters to personally
supervise the hotel this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephanie Perry, 30, of Lakeland, said the heavy police
presence at the hotel and a written code of conduct passed out to
guests upon check-in were unique to Black College Reunion and she
hadn't seen them other times she was at the hotel. The code of
conduct put out by the city warns against public nudity and
carrying undomesticated animals, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are little differences you notice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Reynolds, a 22-year-old visitor from Miami, said he had to
get a white friend to order registration information over the phone
because hotel clerks wouldn't send him the information when he
called.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they must balance the safety of the guests while
not appearing to target Black College Reunion. The 16-year-old
event is known for clogging beachside traffic and complaints of
lewdness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0023 </TRAILER>
