<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Supreme Court Justice Resigns  </HEADLINE>
By HOLLY RAMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- An associate justice of the New Hampshire
Supreme Court has resigned after prosecutors concluded he broke the
law by trying to improperly influence the assignment of judges
hearing his divorce case.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general on Friday also said the court's chief
justice broke the law just by listening to Associate Justice
Stephen Thayer, who will not be prosecuted in exchange for stepping
down.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer, 54, tried to influence the selection of substitute
judges when his own divorce case came before the high court,
Attorney General Philip McLaughlin said. The regular justices
disqualified themselves from hearing the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   At a court meeting on Feb. 4, Chief Justice David Brock said he
had appointed two substitutes, including retired Superior Court
Judge George Pappagianis. According to the attorney general's
report, Thayer immediately objected, saying, ''Oh no, don't do
that. Not Pappagianis.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's clerk later said Brock told him to ''slow this
down'' and not tell Pappagianis he had been appointed, but the
clerk already had done so.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin said Brock, by listening to Thayer, broke a law that
prohibits judges from hearing privately from anyone involved in a
case. There is no criminal penalty for violating that law, however.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin concluded that Thayer violated two laws: improper
influence, a felony, and official oppression, a misdemeanor.
However, he said Thayer would not be prosecuted in return for his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer's lawyer, William Brennan, said Friday his client's
actions were not criminal and that a trial would have led to his
''complete vindication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
