<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cafe Refers to Seattle Boom  </HEADLINE>
By LUIS CABRERA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- The name Boomtown Cafe was a natural, Anthony
Anderson says, in this high-tech mecca where millionaires have been
sprouting like mushrooms for the last dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson's eatery, which offers an entree, green salad and
beverage for a mere $1.75, is more interested in catering to those
still busted amid the boom.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea is to be able to provide people with a meal that's
nutritious, in a manner that is dignified, instead of having people
stand in line with a tray (in a shelter) and eat food that's
unrecognizable,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, the former manager of Windows on the World atop New
York's World Trade Center, is part of a group of homeless advocates
and food workers who endeavored for five years to raise money and
find a site for the private, nonprofit cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great thing to be able to sit down and be served, and
also to be able to buy a meal for a friend,'' says Bob Kubiniec,
cafe co-founder and associate director of Real Change, the city's
twice-monthly newspaper about the homeless, who also sell copies of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like a four-star restaurant'' compared to eating at a
homeless shelter, said patron Brian Hopkins, 33, indicating the
half-dozen or so tables flanked by wall booths, each adorned with a
fresh-cut daffodil.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins came in for the lasagna with garlic bread. Other entree
choices were squash soup or a meatball sub, with a salad and drink.
</P>
<P>
   The salad was crisp and artfully arranged with carrot strips,
cucumber slices and freshly grated Parmesan cheese. The sub came
open-face on a sesame-seed bun, smothered with melted cheese, red
sauce and more Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson feels the quality of the food and presentation is
''extremely important.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Wippel, spokesman for the nearby Union Gospel Mission, says
his clients have nothing but good things to say about the Boomtown
Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ''The place is clean, and it's certainly in the right spot,
right in the middle of where all the people who are homeless
reside. I just think it's great,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The cafe is located in downtown Seattle, near a park popular
with the homeless and near several shelters and low-income hotels.
It also sits across the street from the King County Courthouse and
another public building, and some of the skirt-and-blazer crowd
does drop in, Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   Cafe organizers gained operational insight from the pioneering
Sisters of the Road cafe in Portland, Ore., and they took
inspiration from John Steinbeck's ''The Grapes of Wrath,'' reading
it together as they finalized their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Joad family was drawn across the country by these signs
that were put all over saying 'work available,' the streets were
paved with gold. They put all they had in the car and trekked out
to find that was not the case,'' Kubiniec says.
</P>
<P>
   He says the situation is somewhat similar in present-day
Seattle, where Microsoft alone is estimated to have produced as
many as 10,000 new millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's drawing people by creating dreams of wealth that ain't
delivering for everyone,'' Kubiniec says.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers make up much of the cafe staff, often including those
who can't afford the price of a meal but are willing to lend a hand
with dishes, break down boxes or do other chores, Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   Those who won't work, however, won't eat.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's difficult,'' he said. ''We want to be compassionate, but
we don't ever want to give someone something for nothing, because
there's not a whole lot of respect in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.boomtowncafe.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0108 </TRAILER>
