<HEADLINE> The Sheiks Headed for Derby Again  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The sheiks are ready to give the Kentucky Derby
another try.
<TEXT>
<P>
   China Visit, owned by the Godolphin Stable of sheiks Maktoum al
Maktoum and Mohammed al Maktoum, is being pointed toward the Derby
on May 6 at Churchill Downs, racing manager Simon Crisford said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Skeikh Maktoum is very keen to go for the Kentucky Derby with
his home-bred colt, China Visit,'' Crisford, Godolphin's racing
manager, said. ''We are hoping that Chief Seattle will also be able
to take part in the Kentucky Derby and we are now planning their
shipping arrangements.''
</P>
<P>
   China Visit, with Richard Hills aboard, won the first United
Arab Emirates Derby on March 25 at Nad Al Sheba Racecourse in
Dubai. In just his second career start, China Visit beat Bachir by
4 1-4 lengths in the 1[-mile race on dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The colt, along with Godolphin-owned Curule -- third in the UAE
Derby -- will be nominated for the Triple Crown races on Saturday at
a cost of $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Seattle, who finished second to Anees in the Breeders' Cup
Juvenile last November, was purchased by Godolphin from William
Betz and Phillip Needham. He has yet to race this year, but may run
in a trial race at Nad Al Sheba to prepare for Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the first time the Makhtoum family sent a horse to
the Derby. Its Worldy Manner finished seventh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
