<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Carolina Looks To Shield Tobacco  </HEADLINE>
By ESTES THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- North Carolina, the nation's No. 1
tobacco-producing state, is joining other states trying to shield
the tobacco industry from feared bankruptcy that could occur with a
possible $300 billion verdict in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Already, three states -- Virginia, Kentucky and Georgia -- have
approved laws to cap the bond a company must pay to appeal a damage
award. Under Florida law, the appealing party must post a bond
equal to the amount of damages awarded by the jury to protect the
plaintiff's right to collect.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt has called a special session of the
Legislature for Wednesday to consider a proposed cap on appeal
bonds a state-based company must pay.
</P>
<P>
   Republican state Rep. Rex Baker, representing tobacco factory
workers and farmers in northwestern North Carolina, said the
financial risks to tobacco companies ''are so high, we can't take a
chance of a judge being irrational.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, a former R.J. Reynolds executive, said he fears a $300
billion appeal bond could endanger the $100 million in state taxes
generated by North Carolina's tobacco industry, which produced
449.6 million pounds of tobacco last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the tobacco industry had to post such a bond, there's no
way it could be done,'' Baker said. ''The only way they could
prevent that from happening is to declare bankruptcy. It would be
absolutely devastating. It's the end of tobacco as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Banzhaf, a law professor and director of Action on Smoking
and Health, said the intent of lawsuits isn't to put tobacco
companies out of business. ''That's their scare story ... to
influence legislators to pass legislation designed to protect
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The protection rankles anti-tobacco forces and troubles some
constitutional law scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clearly unconstitutional,'' said Richard Daynard, a
Northeastern University law professor and director of a group that
encourages lawsuits against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   He said it violates the full faith and credit clause of the U.S.
Constitution, which requires states to recognize each other's court
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents like North Carolina's governor and attorney
general say it is an economic necessity in North Carolina. Tobacco
generates nearly $1 billion for North Carolina farmers and 114,000
people are employed in tobacco-related jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia and Georgia approved a $25 million limit; Kentucky set
it at $100 million. North Carolina is considering a $25 million
cap.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, a Democrat, said that the measure is needed not just to
preserve the tobacco industry but to ensure that states continue to
get their annual payments from the $246 billion nationwide
settlement with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   A Florida jury found last year that cigarette companies --
including R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., Liggett Group and Lorillard
Tobacco Co., all three of which are based in North Carolina -- made
a deadly product. The jury is now considering how much compensatory
damages to award three representative plaintiffs in the class
action. If it awards compensatory damages, it then will weigh
punitive damages for all of the smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hunt: http://www.governor.state.nc.us/news/releases
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds: http://www.rjrt.com
</P>
<P>
   Lorillard: http://www.lorillard.net
</P>
<P>
   Liggett: http://www.brookegroup.com
</P>
<P>
   American Lung Association: http://www.lungusa.org/tobacco
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0134 </TRAILER>
