<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brunei Prince Rudely Awakened  </HEADLINE>
By RANJAN ROY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) -- For generations, every child
in Brunei heard the legend of how a glittering mountain of gold
that stood to feed the kingdom vanished beneath the seas to punish
a wasteful and indifferent people.
</P>
<P>
   Now that tale may be replaced by a real story -- of a prodigal
prince who set forth to conquer the world, buying skyscrapers,
diamonds, yachts and fast jets; a prince who may not live happily
ever after.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah, whose family has ruled the sultanate on
the northern tip of Borneo for 600 years, found sometime in 1998
that the cupboards containing the nation's oil riches were bare.
</P>
<P>
   The keys were with his youngest brother, Prince Jefri Bolkiah,
who until then had controlled the finance ministry and as chairman
of the Brunei Investment Agency was responsible for investing the
nation's oil money overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the tiny sultanate surrounded by offshore oil reserves --
its golden mountain -- has been rudely awakened to economic reality
and its people exposed to the depths of royal extravagance.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Jefri and his flagship company Amedeo reportedly
squandered an estimated $16 billion in 10 years. Nobody in Brunei
knows exactly how much money was lost, but it has been large enough
to affect the entire nation at a time when revenues were stretched
by low oil prices and the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The government is prosecuting Jefri for wasting the nation's
wealth. His passport was impounded and he is a virtual prisoner in
his palace on the outskirts of the capital, adjacent to a
Disneyland-like amusement park he created.
</P>
<P>
   Jefri lives on a stipend of $300,000 a month, which his lawyers
say is paltry by the prince's royal standards and given that he has
four wives and 35 children to support.
</P>
<P>
   The government, meanwhile, is trying to get back some of the
squandered wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Brunei's High Court asked Jefri last month to disclose his
assets, which even corporate detectives hired by Brunei in London
have not been able to fully assess.
</P>
<P>
   In an interim ruling in the civil suit filed by the Brunei
Investment Agency against Jefri and 71 others -- including his son --
Chief Justice Denys Roberts said Jefri spent $2.7 billion just on
aircraft, yachts, cars and jewelry. ''This suggests a lifestyle of
great extravagance,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings have so far been closed. But once a trial begins, Jefri
may be forced to appear to defend himself from accusations that he
squandered money in a lavish lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Debris from his once-starry empire dot Bandar Seri Begawan in
the form of half-finished and abandoned office buildings, their
scaffolding still attached. Some of the world's most prestigious
hotels, the Plaza Athenee in Paris, the New York Palace, the
Dorchester Hotel in London and the Bel-Air in Los Angeles, all
believed to be owned by Jefri, may be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed quickly for the prince in the last two
years. The last time he was dragged to a court was when beauty
contestants filed a suit in 1998 alleging they had been brought to
Brunei and held against their will. The royal family denied the
charge and the court accepted Jefri's immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Brunei, with a population of 300,000, is still a rich country.
Its per capita gross domestic product of $20,100 is close to that
of Germany, Japan and Hong Kong -- and no one pays taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Sultan himself is rarely seen in person, only on television,
lit to appear in an Islamic and statesman-like way. He stays in a
palace with his first wife, while the second has a palace of her
own on the outskirts of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows when they flit in and out in their private jets,
but everyone has heard about the designer clothes, the BMWs and
Jaguars and the prize horses in air-conditioned stables.
</P>
<P>
   There is no parliament, no annual budgets are presented, no
balance sheets disclosed. No one is allowed to question the divine
authority of the sultans, and the former British protectorate
exists in a ''state of emergency'' imposed 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody knows how much the palace spends and how much money
Brunei earns from oil,'' said a Western diplomat in Bandar Seri
Begawan. ''We can only guess because the whole thing is shrouded in
secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jefri's case is beginning to change attitudes toward royalty
among younger, Internet-savvy Bruneians who have studied and
traveled overseas.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, newspapers are gleefully discussing Jefri's
allegedly wanton ways, giving residents a glimpse of life behind
the high walls of the palaces. A new Web site is bombarded with
letters asking how Bruneians feel about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Although people on the street still balk at the idea of
discussing the Bolkiahs with foreigners, they are beginning to do
so increasingly among themselves, local journalists said.
</P>
<P>
   But few expect a cascade of changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government is only showing that nobody is above the law,''
said Hatta Bin Zainal Abidin, leader of the Solidarity Nation
Party, an inactive political group that is the closest to a
political party in Brunei. ''It's still a family matter.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
