<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volcano Erupts Twice in N. Japan  </HEADLINE>
By KOJI SASAHARA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- Northern Japan's Mount Usu spit out ash and
debris in two more major eruptions today, raising fears among
thousands of evacuees that they will be living at makeshift
shelters far longer than they thought.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Meteorological Agency said one of the eruptions
occurred before dawn today, and neither was believed to be as
intense as the initial eruption Friday, when the volcano came to
life after more than two decades of silence.
</P>
<P>
   But officials warned more were probably in store.
</P>
<P>
   ''Volcanic activities are intensifying and even larger eruptions
than the previous ones are highly likely,'' said agency official
Toshimitsu Niibe. ''We just don't know exactly how soon that will
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Niibe urged residents and officials near the volcano, on the
northernmost main island of Hokkaido, to stay alert.
</P>
<P>
   Life for the more than 11,000 people forced to evacuate their
homes was growing increasingly difficult. Many evacuated several
days ago as earthquakes intensified prior to the eruption.
</P>
<P>
   ''I experienced the last eruption too, so I was prepared and
evacuated right away,'' said Yuko Takahashi, a nursing home
employee, referring to the last time the volcano erupted, in 1978.
''But I wonder how long we have to live like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have reported no damage or injuries from any of the
eruptions, although rice fields and other crops have been dusted
with a blanket of fine, volcanic ash.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuations left the nearby town of Abuta deserted except
for a few dogs wandering the streets. Some pets were left tied by
their owners, who assumed the evacuation would end soon.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that was not likely, and were also not ready to
allow even brief visits to check the homes.
</P>
<P>
   Haruo Imamoto, a garbage collector in Abuta, was worrying about
his livelihood after the eruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now the town is deserted I don't even have a job,'' he said
today from an evacuation center. ''Who knows how long it's going to
last -- a week, maybe even months? I'm worried about my job, but
there is nothing I can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said that evacuees might have to
stay for a while at makeshift centers set up in school gyms and
community halls. The government will consider building temporary
housing if that is the case, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the centers, families sat on blankets spread out to mark
their private space. Some put up cardboard partitions, but there
was little else to give them any sense of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's explosion came with barely a sound, sending a
spectacular blue-gray plume of molten rock and ash billowing above
the crater and rolling down the snow-quilted slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Ash fluttered down and dusted ghostly silent, evacuated
villages. Sirens screaming warnings echoed through the empty
streets as ambulances and police cars cruised in search of damage.
</P>
<P>
   Farther away from the volcano, people climbed to rooftops to
watch the towering cloud that blossomed from the eruption Friday.
Some snapped photographs of the billowing debris and gas that rose
to a height of two miles.
</P>
<P>
   Falling snow increased concerns about mudslides in the lakeside
resort area. The military was called in because of concerns over
the possibility of landslides or mudslides caused by melting
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Mudslides triggered by Usu's last eruptions killed two people
and destroyed 200 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Fears also remained that Usu could spew a deadly mix of gas and
rocks -- called a pyroclastic flow -- that races down slopes and
incinerates everything in its path.
</P>
<P>
   About 51,000 people live in the coastal city of Date and several
smaller towns near Usu, 475 miles north of Tokyo. Experts had
predicted the eruption because of increased seismic activity that
began earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is one of the world's most eruption-prone countries, with
86 active volcanoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
