<HEADLINE> Political Donor Charged in NJ Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A grand jury has charged political donor
David Chang with funneling nearly $23,000 in illegal donations to
Sen. Robert Torricelli's 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, a 55-year-old businessman, also was charged Friday with
contacting a grand jury witness earlier in the week and encouraging
him to lie.
</P>
<P>
   The donor and his political aide, Audrey Yu, were charged in
December with conspiring to obstruct a federal investigation into
campaign finance abuses in Torricelli's campaign by destroying
records from one of his companies.
</P>
<P>
   Chang is to be arraigned on the new charges on April 15. His
April 25 trial is still set to go on as scheduled. If convicted of
all charges, he faces up to 80 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Chang has an unpublished telephone number and could not be
reached Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli's ability to raise $9.2 million in a 1996 race he won
over Rep. Richard A. Zimmer helped him be appointed to his current
position as chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department task force investigating campaign finance
abuses has since secured three guilty pleas from Torricelli
contributors who said they made illegal donations to the campaign,
and the indictments of Chang and Yu.
</P>
</TEXT>
