<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 Injured in N.J. Bus Accident  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALLOWAY TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- Seventeen people were injured
when a minibus taking gamblers to an Atlantic City casino
rear-ended a truck on the Garden State Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   Two remained hospitalized in critical condition. The others
suffered minor injuries, state police said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucky Strike Travel Service Inc. minibus, with 17 people
aboard, left from New York's Chinatown section and was bound for
Bally's Park Place Casino Hotel when the accident occurred about 10
miles northwest of Atlantic City, Trooper Barry Saul said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, Guang Zhi Chi, 29, told police that he was in the
right lane on the southbound side of the parkway when he pulled out
to pass a slower-moving vehicle, Saul said. The minibus rammed the
rear of a truck in the left lane. The two people in the truck
suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The bus passengers were mostly in their 60s and 70s, but one was
17 years old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0222 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland's Police Face Questions  </HEADLINE>
By MONIKA SCISLOWSKA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Panicky police open fire on an escaped
tiger and end up killing a veterinarian. Mayhem erupts in a
courtroom after gang members smuggle grenades past police guards
into their own extortion trial. Officers blow up half an apartment
building trying to flush out a pair of murder suspects.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just this month. Little wonder that many Poles, who
feared police as a force of repression under the old communist
regime, now wonder whether the officers are up to their new role as
protectors.
</P>
<P>
   The police, for their part, beg understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ninety-nine percent of our actions are done correctly, but
only mistakes are noticed,'' said Pawel Biedziak, spokesman for
Poland's national police force. ''The police are like society: We
face similar problems like ordinary people.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the collapse of communist rule in 1989, the once-powerful
police force has struggled to cope with increasingly bold
criminals, chronic funding shortages, poor training and a lack of
modern equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do their woes come so embarrassingly into focus as last
week, when officers chased down an escaped circus tiger in a Warsaw
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   With television cameras catching the action, the tiger turned on
a veterinarian who had shot a tranquilizer dart at the animal. The
officers opened fire -- killing the doctor. They managed to kill the
tiger a short time later, but that was little consolation. Three
officers now face disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, in the southwestern Polish city of Jelenia Gora,
gang members on trial for extortion managed to smuggle grenades
into the courtroom. After at least two exploded, anti-terrorist
police ended the melee by fatally shooting two of the defendants. A
special commission faulted guards who failed to search the
defendants after their repeated trips to the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   In the Baltic port city of Szczecin, police overestimated the
explosive punch needed to blow open an apartment door. The
resulting blast caused extensive damage to the apartment building,
leaving the state with $50,000 repair bill.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, Biedziak said police answer 5,000 calls daily
across Poland, usually without serious problems, and use weapons in
only about 100 cases a year. He also noted that police have made
solid progress against drug trafficking and organized crime, with
some major arrests in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   But government officials concede that this month's string of
highly publicized blunders reflect more than a mere run of bad
luck.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Marek Biernacki acknowledged after the tiger
fiasco that police are unprepared for such emergencies, and ordered
that revised procedures be developed.
</P>
<P>
   Police complain about lack of training, sluggish courts and a
crime wave that washed over them in the sudden liberal atmosphere
that followed the collapse of communism in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The police force has changed as well. Gone are the elite
security forces that kept order under communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''The transfer from (communist) militia to police has cost them
professionalism,'' argues one ex-communist politician and former
police officer, Jerzy Dziewulski.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, low pay -- averaging $480 a month for experienced
policemen -- has caused the best-trained officers to seek better
jobs elsewhere, Biedziak said. Starting pay of just $165 also makes
it tough to find good recruits.
</P>
<P>
   A report last year by a state Supreme Chamber of Control
complained that police have no clear requirements for candidates,
and that training is too heavy on theory and not enough on
practical police technique.
</P>
<P>
   Biedziak said motivation tests now result in the rejection of 80
percent of potential recruits, and practical training has replaced
the theory-based training methods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0223 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wisconsin Looking To Upset Mich. St  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Wisconsin Badgers are trying pull off
their own version of ''Hoosiers.'' They've come to the right place.
</P>
<P>
   Milan High School's improbable state championship, chronicled in
the movie starring Gene Hackman, was won in Indianapolis. The
Badgers have even practiced at Hinkle Fieldhouse, where that famous
game was played 46 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've seen the movie at least 17 or 18 times,'' Wisconsin coach
Dick Bennett said Friday. ''I like Gene Hackman as an actor, always
have. I thought he was especially good in that movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett can't find his copy of ''Hoosiers,'' and he didn't bring
a ladder to Indy, either. Too bad. In the movie, Hackman climbed to
the rim, pulled out a tape measure and showed his players that the
basket at Hinkle was 10 feet high, just like any other court.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I eyeballed the rim,'' Bennett conceded, ''and it was 10
feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Badgers (22-13), they'll be playing at the
RCA Dome instead of the historic fieldhouse today when they meet
Michigan State (30-7) in the national semifinals. Wisconsin needs
all the help it can get after losing three times to the Spartans
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is there a seed of doubt?'' Bennett said. ''I would be lying
if I said there wasn't. When a team beats you three times, you can
say that's a superior team.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should anyone believe the fourth meeting of the season
between these Big Ten rivals will be any different than the first
three? Michigan State routed the Badgers 61-44 in Madison in
February; Wisconsin played more respectably in losing the next two
meetings 59-54 and 55-46, the latter in the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans, the only top seed to reach Indy, began thinking
about winning their first national championship in 21 years as soon
as the horn sounded on their Final Four loss to Duke last season.
</P>
<P>
   A third straight Big Ten title wasn't enough. Mateen Cleaves,
one of the nation's best point guards, skipped a chance to play in
the NBA for this moment.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't come alone. The supporting cast -- A.J. Granger,
Morris Peterson, Andre Hutson and Charlie Bell -- is experienced and
title-worthy. The team is versatile on offense, stifling on defense
and highly motivated. The Spartans are the unquestioned favorite at
this Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't really believe it totally, but I do embrace it,''
coach Tom Izzo said. ''This team can handle it. We've had the
bull's-eye on us for an entire year.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Wisconsin, which wasn't even one of the four best
teams in its own conference. The Badgers finished sixth in the Big
Ten, but they've won 11 of their last 14 games -- all three losses
coming against Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   ''To win this next game, most people think it's improbable,''
Wisconsin forward Andy Kowske said. ''We just go out and play
defense. That's our confidence right there, our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, defense. Bennett's turn-back-the-clock style of play
focuses on stopping the other team -- not a bunch of crowd-pleasing,
high-flying dunks. The Badgers have reached the 70s only four times
all season.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly? Sure. Effective? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We play the style of game that we have to play,'' Kowske said.
''If we tried to run and gun, everyone would run right by us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers are well aware of what they must do to reach Monday
night's title game against the North Carolina-Florida winner -- slow
things down offensively, never let up defensively, get down and
dirty on the boards. This is no time for a radical change.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are certain things we need to do better,'' Bennett said.
''But a change philosophically is certainly not an issue. We need
to be who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State expects nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   ''Teams like Wisconsin, you don't enjoy playing them,'' Cleaves
said. ''Unfortunately, we have to play them.''
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
