<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Democrats worried about Giuliani fund raising lead  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rudolph Giuliani's $7 million fund-raising
lead over Hillary Rodham Clinton has some Democrats uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so long ago that Democrats were confidently predicting
the first lady would fill a $25 million Senate war chest and the
New York City mayor was painting himself as a cash-starved
underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know that we're going to be outspent,'' Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle said Friday. ''The question is, can we keep that
gap as narrow as is possible, and that's going to take a real
concerted effort.'' Daschle met with Clinton about her campaign
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani raised about $7 million during the first three months
of this year, in addition to nearly $12 million he raised last
year. Clinton raised a little over $4 million for the Jan. 1
through March 31 period, in addition to the $8 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jordan, political director for the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee, said the party needed to refocus it's efforts
on New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of us in the party need to be concerned about what
Giuliani has raised,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe Democrats have been complacent about her needs,'' Jordan
said. ''Maybe we underestimated the fund-raising powers of the
mayor of the richest city in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's operation declined comment but appeared at
least a little nervous by the totals.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, after Giuliani released his tally, an e-mail went
out from the Clinton campaign appealing for last-minute
contributions over the Internet before the close of the campaign
filing period Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is still time to send a signal that you reject Rudy
Giuliani's negative tactics and support Hillary's positive
message,'' the letter from Clinton campaign manager Bill de Blasio
said. ''We have 24 more hours in this filing.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail letter asked the recipient to forward the letter to
five friends.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani camp used the same tactic as the close of the last
filing period neared, Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum, reached as the
mayor raised even more money in Arizona on Friday, said the totals
demonstrate ''sagging support for her campaign, while our numbers
suggest just the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising news for Giuliani came as Clinton pulled even
with him in the polls. Those surveys showed the mayor had been hurt
by his handling of the police shooting of Patrick Dorismond.
</P>
<P>
   Still, New York Republican consultant Jay Severin said
Giuliani's cash lead was an embarrassment that indicated Clinton's
campaign was ''not ready for prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Democrats should not have been surprised by this,'' he
said. ''They should have been better equipped and they should have
been stronger out of the gate, especially with an untested
first-time candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultant Hank Sheinkopf predicted Clinton would
have the money she needed for the race and said Giuliani's cash
lead ''will energize the Democratic party elders to get things
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Severin or Sheinkopf is involved in the Senate contest.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's $19 million shattered fund-raising records in New
York set when then-Rep. Charles Schumer defeated incumbent Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato in 1998. Giuliani has already raised more money
than Schumer raised in total for that race, which cost a total of
$35 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer noted Friday that money isn't always an indicator of
success.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al D'Amato outspent me and I won,'' Schumer said. ''In a
high-profile race it's your views that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Schumer's win over D'Amato, there have been other
occasions where the candidate with the most money has failed to
win. Oliver North's better-financed campaign against U.S. Sen.
Charles Robb of Virginia failed. So did Michael Huffington's bid
against U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein of California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
