<HEADLINE> China Bars Snow's Widow From Meeting  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN LEICESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Filmed and tailed by Chinese security agents, the
widow of famed American journalist Edgar Snow tried today to
deliver money, a book and moral support to a woman whose son was
killed in the 1989 Tiananmen Square crackdown. Authorities
prevented the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Snow had hoped that a meeting with Ding Zilin, who has
campaigned for victims of the crackdown, would focus Chinese
leaders' attention on the plight of Ding and the scores of others
like her who have never received compensation or an official
apology for the deaths of their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   But plainclothes agents followed Snow's car from her hotel to
the People's University where Ding lives, swerved in front of the
car when it pulled up at the school gates and watched and filmed
while Snow, her son and a family friend tried to go inside.
</P>
<P>
   With plainclothes agents in sunglasses hovering nearby,
university security officials barred the way and told the Snows and
a friend of Ding's who met them at the gate that they could not
come in without official permission.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the campus, meanwhile, around a dozen security agents
prevented Ding, a retired professor, from leaving her home, Ding
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''They told me: 'You can't go out,' '' she said. ''I said, 'How
can you be so cruel? She's an old friend of China.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Snow, who arrived Friday, had not visited China since the
Tiananmen Square crackdown because of her anger over the bloodshed.
Her decision to come back to meet Ding, and to visit her husband's
grave, presented an embarrassing challenge to the authorities
because of Edgar Snow's renown in China for his reporting of the
Communist Party's long struggle to take power.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, Edgar Snow became the first Western journalist to
interview Mao Tse-tung and other communist leaders when they were
still known as ''Red Bandits,'' fighting a guerrilla war that
finally overthrew the Nationalists in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Snow, 79, lives in Switzerland. She first came to China in 1970
with her husband, on what was to be his last visit before his death
in 1972. She met Mao and Premier Zhou Enlai, the leaders Snow
described vividly in his 1937 book ''Red Star Over China,'' which
focused international attention on the then-struggling Chinese
communist movement.
</P>
<P>
   Ding, meanwhile, has led a quiet campaign to seek redress from
the government for the crackdown on democracy protesters in 1989,
in which hundreds or possibly thousands of people, including Ding's
17-year-old son, Jiang Jielian, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite frequent police harassment, Ding has collected the names
of victims and distributed donations from abroad to victims'
families.
</P>
<P>
   Because she was unable to meet Ding in person, Snow gave a book
of photos taken by her husband as well as an envelope of money and
a statement of support to the friend who met her, Su Bingxian, who
also lost a son in the crackdown. Su said she would pass them on to
Ding.
</P>
<P>
   Snow signed the book ''To Ding Zilin and all the mothers, in
friendship and admiration ... Hoping to see you in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Chinese authorities are always saying Edgar Snow is a
friend of China,'' said Snow's son, Chris. ''I don't feel this is a
friendly way to behave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0251 </TRAILER>
