<DOCNO> APW20000401.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kelley Defines Wisconsin's D  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Dick Bennett came to Mike Kelley preaching
self-sacrifice, teamwork and defense. Unlike many blue-chip
recruits, Kelley listened and believed.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, the Wisconsin Badgers' junior point guard, has become a
walking, talking and (sometimes) hacking defensive star. On a team
stocked with above-average defenders and built around a suffocating
style, Kelley is the stopper.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love the way we play,'' Kelley said. ''I think it's
beautiful. To the outside observer who isn't a part of our program,
I think it's viewed as ugly by many people, but I don't know how
you can't enjoy that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers' trip to the Final Four and today's meeting with
Michigan State are due in no small part to Kelley, the two-time Big
Ten defensive player of the year. He has a formula for playing the
kind of defense coaches love but players usually have no time for.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's nothing fancy,'' Kelley said. ''It's just working hard
and waiting for your opportunities. You've got to watch and wait.
These days, not many players like to work that hard, and not many
players like to wait that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley has almost as many steals (93) as field-goal attempts
(94) this season. A junior, he already owns Wisconsin's career
steals record. He plays so aggressively his own coach criticized
him for trying too hard for loose balls and errant passes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the toughest thing about Kelley is getting him to take
credit for his efforts. If not for his suffocating play against
Purdue star Jaraan Cornell in four games this year, the Badgers'
season would have ended long before this.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin split with Purdue during the regular season, but beat
the Boilermakers in the Big Ten tournament and in the West Regional
final. In those four games, Kelley held Cornell to a total of 26
points on 9-for-42 shooting (21 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Kelley was constantly in Cornell's face, holding him, pushing
him, fouling him hard when the occasion demanded. In all three
losses, Cornell nearly snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was swearing, saying he was going to break my nose, all
this stuff,'' Kelley laughed. ''I think we might have been under
his skin a little bit -- OK, a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley hasn't been as effective against Michigan State's Mateen
Cleaves in the Badgers' three losses to the Spartans this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''We respect their defense a lot, because it's probably one of
the best ones we faced,'' Cleaves said. ''Kelley is a great
defensive player. We have to play even a notch harder against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley is probably the Badgers' most recognizable player -- which
isn't saying much for a bunch that puts team first and failed to
place even one player on the Big Ten's honorable mention list. But
Bennett has no problem singling out Kelley, his on-court leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has the greatest capacity for concentration of any player
I've been around,'' Bennett said. ''He's able to focus on what he
needs to do for every second he's in the game. He doesn't get down
when he gets beat. He just dusts himself off and goes right to work
on beating you again.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Kelley said he accepted a scholarship to play for Bennett
''before he could even offer it,'' their relationship hasn't always
been harmonious. When Kelley put himself on the bench because of
foul trouble in several consecutive games in January, Bennett
called him selfish and too concerned about breaking Wisconsin's
career steals record.
</P>
<P>
   The rift healed quickly, but Kelley continued fighting for every
scrap on every defensive stand. He played in the conference
tournament with a painful thigh bruise and stitches to close a gash
near his eye. His ankles were sore all season. He sprained several
fingers and got his thumb stuck under somebody's sneaker.
</P>
<P>
   ''He sees things on the floor that I don't see,'' forward Andy
Kowske said. ''He anticipates so well. You put all that together in
a point guard, and you're going to get a lot of steals.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this team didn't have him, we wouldn't be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0254 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mich St. Players Form Partnership  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY ATKINS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The longer he stays in the business, the
less Tom Izzo needs to hear the sound of his own voice.
</P>
<P>
   ''My players have a partnership in this team,'' he said. ''It's
not a dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo has guided Michigan State to three straight Big Ten
championships and a second straight Final Four berth. But he's not
above listening to his players, even at the biggest moments. Last
week, for example, in the Midwest Regional championship against
Iowa State, star forward Morris Peterson suggested an alley-oop
play during a late timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ''That sounds great,'' Izzo said.
</P>
<P>
   When play resumed, the Spartans ran the play, and Peterson
delivered the crucial basket. As a result, Michigan State (30-7)
will play Wisconsin (22-13) today for the fourth time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think a lot of coaches, they don't really let their players
get involved in some of their plays,'' Peterson said. ''I think
that's what kind of separates coach Izzo. He can really relate to
his players.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's always willing to listen to them and get some of their
input.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo also holds his players accountable -- for their dreams as
well as his own. Peterson and point guard Mateen Cleaves both want
to play in the NBA. Izzo has pushed the two seniors hard to make
sure they make it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We set up the game plan to get them there,'' Izzo said. ''If
they deviate from that game plan and I didn't say something, I
would be cheating them out of an opportunity of a lifetime and a
dream.
</P>
<P>
   ''And that's the way I look at it. So we have a common respect.
I have my dreams and goals and I think they do, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo brought the Spartans to Indianapolis on Wednesday night,
long before they needed to be in town. A sure sign Izzo was getting
a little nervous, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not at all.
</P>
<P>
   After a light workout at a nearby college gym, Izzo turned his
players loose. He told them to go have fun. Naturally, Cleaves, the
heart of this team, steered most of the players downtown to watch --
what else? -- a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a great coach-player relationship,'' Cleaves said.
''He lets his players have input on what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That unity of purpose might be one reason why the Spartans have
been able to come back from deep deficits to win their last three
tournament games. The coach and his players almost always think
alike.
</P>
<P>
   ''I try to treat people like I'd want to be treated myself, and
my parents,'' Izzo said. ''You have a responsibility to do your
job.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am what I am, and I can't hide that. I'm honest with my
players about that. I'm honest with them when I recruit them.''
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean Izzo won't crack down now and then. He will.
</P>
<P>
   In order to teach Peterson a lesson during his freshman year,
Izzo left him home while the rest of the team traveled to a
tournament in Hawaii. Izzo also has disciplined the fun-loving
Cleaves a couple of times over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the few misfortunes he's had, you know, adversity
sometimes brings you closer,'' Izzo said.
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with Cleaves is especially important to Izzo.
For one thing, Cleaves was his first big-time recruit. For another,
Cleaves is the point guard, a position Izzo views as a coach on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it was Izzo's position during his own playing days.
</P>
<P>
   ''For all those reasons, I think the relationship has grown,''
Izzo said. ''And it's like all relationships, not always perfect,
but I have great respect for him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have great respect for his ability to come to practice day
in, day out and be the hardest worker and a guy that really lays it
on the line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0254 </TRAILER>
