<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China Bars Snow's Widow From Meeting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Filmed and tailed by Chinese security agents, the widow of
famed American journalist Edgar Snow tried Saturday to deliver money, a book and
moral support to a woman whose son was killed in the 1989 Tiananmen Square
crackdown. Authorities prevented the meeting. Lois Snow had hoped that a meeting
with Ding Zilin, who has campaigned for victims of the crackdown, would focus
Chinese leaders' attention on the plight of Ding and the scores of others like
her who have never received compensation or an official apology for the deaths
of their loved ones.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ugandan Death Toll Reaches 924
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- Struggling with a lack of equipment after uncovering
a string of mass graves, police are regrouping before tackling yet another
compound where more victims of a doomsday cult may be buried. The death toll
from the mass killing now stands at 924, after police raised the number who died
when a cult church was set ablaze with hundreds of members sealed inside. Since
then, mass graves at three other compounds have uncovered more bodies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Volcano Erupts Twice in N. Japan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- Northern Japan's Mount Usu spit out ash and debris in two
more major eruptions Saturday, raising fears among thousands of evacuees that
they will be living at makeshift shelters far longer than they thought. The
Central Meteorological Agency said one of the eruptions occurred before dawn
Saturday, and neither was believed to be as intense as the initial eruption
Friday, when the volcano came to life after more than two decades of silence.
But officials warned more were probably in store.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Former Cemetery Director Indicted
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The former director of the historic Congressional Cemetery
has been charged with embezzling more than $175,000 from dozens of cemetery
clients -- including an FBI charity. Federal prosecutors charged in an
indictment that 64-year-old John Hanley used the money to buy racehorses, among
other things. Law enforcers said the theft included a $4,545.80 check in August
1996 intended to help maintain the gravesite of FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover.
Hanley pleaded innocent Friday at a hearing in U.S. District Court in
Washington.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Starr Sets Costly Record
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kenneth Starr's investigation of President Clinton cost
$52 million, the most expensive independent counsel inquiry ever, according
congressional investigators. The General Accounting Office said Starr's
Whitewater and Monica Lewinsky probe exceeded the $47.4 million record set by
Lawrence E. Walsh in the 1980s for the Iran-contra investigation, The Washington
Post reported Saturday. During the past six years, five independent counsels
have spent a total of $95.3 million investigating the Clinton administration,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Father Said Angry for Delay
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A senior Cuban official Friday said Elian Gonzalez's father is
''frustrated'' and ''angry'' by the pace of efforts to reclaim his 6-year-old
son, two and a half months after the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
said he should be reunited with him. The INS has twice moved back deadlines to
revoke the relative's temporary custody pending more negotiations. In Miami,
Elian's relatives Friday said they would let Gonzalez visit him at their Little
Havana home, but that they are no longer willing to give Elian to his father.
They said they would not resist if the government tried to take Elian from their
house.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mich. Boy Denies Shooting Classmate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- With little more than his eyes and nose visible over the
witness stand, a 6-year-old boy Friday denied that he shot classmate Kayla
Rolland to death and blamed another first-grader. The boy testified at a
preliminary hearing for Jamelle James, 19, who is accused of carelessly storing
the semiautomatic handgun that the 6-year-old allegedly found and used to kill
Kayla on Feb. 29. James is charged with involuntary manslaughter; the 6-year-old
isn't charged.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 58.33, Nasdaq Up 114.94
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks edged back from the brink Friday, and the
Nasdaq was up 114.94 at 4,572.83, even though it finished the week 9.4 percent
below its March 10 record high close. The Dow industrials closed down 58.33 at
10,921.92. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led decliners
2,017-1,073.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
SuperSonics Defeat Kings 123-108
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) - Gary Payton had 35 points and 15 assists Friday as the Seattle
SuperSonics ended a five-game homecourt losing streak with a 123-108 victory
over the Sacramento Kings. The Sonics (41-31) moved within a half-game of the
Kings (41-30) in the race for the seventh spot in the Western Conference
standings. The Sonics scored a season-high 69 points in the first half in
rolling to a 20-point lead. The Kings got no closer than 15 during the second
half.
</P>
