<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sindelar Leads BellSouth Classic  </HEADLINE>
By ED SHEARER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DULUTH, Ga. (AP) -- Joey Sindelar is as qualified as anyone to
discuss slumps.
</P>
<P>
   He's been mired in one so far this season, missing the cut in
six events before turning things around to take a one-stroke lead
into today's third round of the BellSouth Classic.
</P>
<P>
   He's gone through other slumps during his first 19 years on the
PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Do they worry him?
</P>
<P>
   ''It depends on what is wrong,'' said Sindelar, who has overcome
a broken wrist and stress fracture in his foot.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the last month and a half, I feel like a guy walking
around and there is a bunch of rakes in the front yard and I keep
stepping on them and hitting myself in the nose.''
</P>
<P>
   Sindelar said he has had slumps where he wasn't playing well and
didn't know where he was going. ''That,'' he said, ''is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   This slump isn't like that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This slump is more of a scoring ability, 'Come on let's get
with it, quit making the dumb mistakes kind.' Got to play your way
through this rather that the ball-striking kind of slump that is
very painful, and I am very happy to not be there.''
</P>
<P>
   His slump hasn't shown itself during his first two trips around
the hilly TPC Sugarloaf layout north of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He shot a 6-under-par 66 on Friday for a 10-under 134 total.
John Huston was second after a 67.
</P>
<P>
   It took an even-par 144 total to make the cut. Seventy-seven
players survived the cut, and one more may join them early today
when Jimmy Green shows up to play the 18th hole. He elected not to
finish Friday when the horn blew to suspend play for darkness. He
stands at 1 under through 17 and needs a bogey or better to survive
the cut.
</P>
<P>
   First-round leader Paul Stankowski and Phil Mickelson were two
strokes back. Stankowski shot a 70, and Mickelson had a 69.
</P>
<P>
   Six others were tied at 137 -- Harrison Frazar with a 68, Dave
Stockton and Gary Nicklaus with 69s and Jean Van de Velde, Blaine
McCallister and Kenny Perry with 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on the back nine, Sindelar parred the first four holes
before putting together consecutive birdies with 8- and 15-foot
putts. He missed a 3{-footer for birdie on No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Sindelar made a 30-foot birdie putt on No. 2, and a 10-footer
No. 3. He made a short birdie putt on No. 7, and closed with a
six-footer on the ninth green.
</P>
<P>
   Huston had seven birdies and two bogeys in his round, sinking
two putts of 20 feet and another from 30 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion David Duval shot a 69 for a 142 total. Greg
Norman, who designed the course, bogeyed his final four holes but
still make the cut with a 144 total. He shot a 73.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, who was two shots off the lead when the day began,
ran into trouble early when he took a 10 on the par-4 fifth hole,
taking two penalty strokes when his ball rolled back off the green
into a creek. He shot a 77 to miss the cut with a 145 total.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
