<HEADLINE> Disoriented Pilot Blamed for Crash  </HEADLINE>
By TOM PARSONS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- The Air Force has determined that the
deaths of three U.S. servicemen during the aborted landing of a
C-130 transport in Kuwait last year stemmed from pilot and crew
error.
</P>
<P>
   The air crew failed to follow procedures and made an improper
approach to a runway, according to Col. Frank Laras. The pilot also
didn't keep an eye on instruments and became disoriented, not
realizing how close the plane was to the ground or how far it was
from the runway at Al Jaber Air Base southwest of Kuwait City, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, yes, he flew the plane into the ground,'' said
Laras, who headed the Air Force investigation of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The plane hit the ground, breaking its landing gear, then flew
back into the air and made an emergency landing without landing
gear on a foam-covered runway at nearby Kuwait International
Airport, Laras said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot and three other crew members could face disciplinary
action by the Air Force, according to Col. Joseph Heimann, a lawyer
with the Air Mobility Command. No decision on that has been made,
he added
</P>
<P>
   The flight engineer has been cleared to resume flying, Laras
said, but the other three remain grounded, performing other duties
at Little Rock Air Force, officials said, pending a decision on
disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, assigned to the 61st Airlift Squadron at the air base
here, was ferrying 86 military passengers the 23 miles from Kuwait
International Airport to Al Jaber before dawn on Dec. 10. Three
passengers were killed when shafts that raise and lower the plane's
main landing gear -- four wheels in the middle of the fuselage --
broke from the impact with the ground and penetrated the plane's
metal skin, according to Laras' report. Also penetrating the
plane's skin, Laras said, were structural beams to which the
landing gear assemblies were attached.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other passengers were injured, two of them critically, the
report said. The two badly injured airmen are expected to recover
completely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0320 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 03:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Sentenced for Hate Attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A man who randomly assaulted a woman on the
street has been sentenced to six years in prison in the first case
of its kind to be prosecuted as a hate crime in California.
</P>
<P>
   A jury on Thursday found that the Aug. 1 attack was motivated by
Billy McCall's hatred of women, which added two years to his
sentence. The victim had been tackled from behind and hit her head
on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The case was the first time the state's hate crime law has been
used to prosecute an offense motivated by the victim's gender. Hate
crime laws usually are applied in cases involving crimes motivated
by race, ethnicity or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, 29, was convicted March 2. His attorney, Karolyn Kovtun,
said an appeal has been filed challenging the use of the hate crime
law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0333 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 03:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYPD has released sealed records before, Safir says  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It had been done before, with no public outcry.
</P>
<P>
   So hours after Patrick Dorismond was fatally shot by police,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir decided
to release the unarmed man's sealed records because of past
experience. In three other cases involving people killed by cops,
those sealed records were unveiled, Safir testified Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''When considering whether to release Mr. (Patrick) Dorismond's
records, it was our understanding that disclosure of the sealed
records was lawful, since the records related to a deceased person
and therefore the records were no longer subject to the sealing
statutes,'' Safir said to the state Assembly committees on codes,
judiciary and children and families at the hearing held at John Jay
College of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts challenged that stance, saying a person's death
did not break the seal on closed records.
</P>
<P>
   Safir seemed perplexed over the amount of attention focused on
Dorismond's records.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the other three cases passed without comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said he released sealed records in another case, and his
predecessor, William Bratton, disclosed records in two other cases.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone, Bratton said he did not have a ''specific
recollection'' of whether or not he released such records.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not saying that it did not occur, and I'm trying to
determine if it did,'' Bratton said, adding that he had placed
telephone calls with his former NYPD staff members to find out. He
did not expect the information to be available on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing focused on the legality of releasing sealed juvenile
records. Hours after Patrick Dorismond was fatally shot by an
undercover detective in Manhattan on March 16, Safir -- with
Giuliani's permission -- told reporters of Dorismond's criminal
history. The 26-year-old was arrested for robbery at age 13 and had
adult arrests for gun possession and assault.
</P>
<P>
   The juvenile case was dismissed and the record sealed; in the
other two cases, Dorismond pleaded guilty to disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of Dorismond's juvenile record outraged his
family, some lawmakers and community residents, and Giuliani and
Safir have been criticized heavily. Public Advocate Mark Green has
obtained a court order seeking a judicial inquiry into the matter.
And on Thursday, a group of clergy members abruptly ended a meeting
with Safir to discuss police and community relations when the
commissioner refused to apologize for releasing Dorismond's record.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani apparently has reached out to another religious
leader. Giuliani met with The Rev. Michel Faulkner at Gracie
Mansion, the New York Daily News reported Friday. In the Thursday
night meeting, Faulkner, a longtime Giuliani backer who recently
condemned the mayor's handling of the Dorismond case, prayed with
the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was reaching out to ''leaders from the
African-American, Haitian community,'' a mayoral aide told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Safir, along with Michael Hess, head of the city's Law
Department, were grilled by Assembly members over their
interpretation of the Family Court Act. The law states that
juvenile records are sealed and not made available to any person or
private agency. The law does not address the issue of what happens
to the records when a person dies. And that's where the dispute is.
</P>
<P>
   The law expires when someone dies, Hess and Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The statute is designed to protect the interests only of the
living,'' Hess said. ''There is no legal basis to apply them to a
deceased person.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts who testified disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never heard of a sealed court record in any court being
unsealed or released without a court order,'' said Merrill Sobie, a
professor at Pace University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ''The statute says the record is sealed, period,'' said Monroe
Freedman, a professor at Hofstra Law School. ''Maybe it should be
amended to say: And Mr. Hess, we really mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Safir, Dorismond's death was investigated by an
NYPD ''shooting team.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In the Dorismond case, the shooting team checked (police)
department systems and learned of two adult arrests and one
juvenile arrest for the decedent,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not ask state court officials or Hess's office for
the records, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The information was then given to Safir in a memo, who then
verbally told Giuliani of Dorismond's record, the commissioner
said. The two then discussed if the record should be disclosed and
decided to do so. Hess was not consulted until after the record was
unsealed.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner also said releasing such information is a
''very rare exception,'' and to his knowledge, has only been done
three other times in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said in April 1997, he released the sealed juvenile record
of 16-year-old Kevin Cedeno, who was fatally shot by police. At the
time of the shooting, Cedeno was on probation for armed robbery,
Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   And when Bratton was commissioner, sealed records were disclosed
after Ernest Sayon, 22, and Anthony Rosario, 18, were fatally shot
by police, Safir said. Sayon was killed in April 1994, Rosario in
January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Safir stood by his reasoning for releasing the records -- to
present all the facts of the shooting to quell any potential
unrest. He disagreed with critics who said the detective who shot
Dorismond did not know about the man's juvenile record.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though the officer was unaware of any arrest record that
night, a person's prior actions can illuminate his or her
personality and help to explain behavior that might otherwise be
inexplicable, and thereby serve to ameliorate what might become an
incident jeopardizing the safety of the public,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul N. Samuels, president of the Legal Action Center in
Manhattan, said the sealing of juvenile records is necessary to
help juvenile delinquents become productive members of society.
</P>
<P>
   ''They make the mistake when they're young,'' Samuels said.
''Unsealing the records does not help them when they've turned
their lives around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-01-00 0346 </TRAILER>
