<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrests at Black College Reunion  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE SCHNEIDER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- While thousands of young men and
women descended on this beach community for Black College Reunion,
local businesses were being monitored for signs of discrimination
against guests.
</P>
<P>
   As the weekend festivities began, police said at least 60 people
were arrested, most for minor infractions such as drug possession
or disorderly conduct. One person was cut with a knife and required
stitches.
</P>
<P>
   ''The arrests that have been made have been for relatively minor
things,'' Volusia County Sheriff Bob Vogel said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal officials and members of the local chapter of
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
scrutinized the Adam's Mark, the area's largest hotel which was
accused of discriminating against black guests during last year's
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel chain recently settled for $8 million two lawsuits
brought by the Justice Department and five former guests and
promised to revise its policies.
</P>
<P>
   Most noticeably, black hotel guests this year weren't required
to wear orange wristbands as they were last year.
</P>
<P>
   Guests were required to pay for their rooms in advance and leave
a $50 deposit to use their room's telephone and snack bar. Adam's
Mark officials said similar conditions are placed on visitors
during other special events, such as spring break.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is nothing that we are doing at this hotel that is out
of the ordinary or that is in any sense racially motivated,'' said
Fred S. Kummer III, Adam's Mark's vice president of corporate
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stephanie Perry, 30, of Lakeland, said the heavy police
presence at the hotel and a written code of conduct passed out to
guests upon check-in were unique to Black College Reunion and she
hadn't seen them other times she was at the hotel. The code of
conduct put out by the city warns against public nudity and
carrying undomesticated animals, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are little differences you notice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel officials said they must balance the safety of the guests
while not appearing to target Black College Reunion. The
16-year-old event is known for clogging beachside traffic and
complaints of lewdness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
