<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland Minimum Wage Takes Effect  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- The Irish Republic's first national
minimum wage came into effect on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The new rate guarantees employees $5.32 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's deputy prime minister, Mary Harney, said the new
minimum wage would benefit more than 160,000 workers nationwide and
''end pay exploitation in the workplace once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It will protect workers who are vulnerable and prone to be
exploited, especially women and young people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 percent of the workers affected by the new minimum wage
will be women, and more than 40 percent will be under the age of
25, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the national wages agreement, the wage will
rise to $5.69 in July next year and $6.05 in October 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
