<HEADLINE> Croatian Warns of Balkans War  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Another war in the Balkans provoked by Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic is a good possibility unless the West
takes steps to stop him, the new Croatian president said in a
magazine interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''Milosevic is like a cyclist that can only keep going as long
as he is riding in the direction of war,'' Stipe Mesic told Der
Spiegel in an interview released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic were to take any action, for example against
Yugoslavia's junior republic Montenegro to keep it a part of the
country, NATO must ''give a very clear signal: 'Milosevic, when you
go into military action against Montenegro, your days are
numbered,''' Mesic said.
</P>
<P>
   Mesic also had strong words against former Croatian
authoritarian leader Franjo Tudjman, whose death made possible the
victory for reformist political forces earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Milosevic doesn't know what Europe is, and Tudjman also didn't
know,'' Mesic said. Tudjman's ''thinking was in the middle ages,
exactly like Milosevic still today.''
</P>
