<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 08:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Troops Find 32 Bodies  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUDERMES, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops today found one injured
survivor and the bodies of 32 servicemen who had been missing after
an ambush by rebels in Chechnya's mountains, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal forces have been sweeping the region of Vedeno, deep in
the southern mountains, for two days in a search for 39 of their
comrades missing after the ambush Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry press service said the 32 bodies and the
injured survivor were found not far from the site of the attack.
Six servicemen remained unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen bodies were recovered, but 13 others had to be left in
the field because they had been mined by rebels, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Yastrzhembsky, the Kremlin spokesman for Chechnya, had
said Friday that 49 Interior Ministry troops were in the convoy
that was ambushed by Chechen rebels near the village of
Zhani-Vedeno, about four miles outside Vedeno. Four soldiers were
killed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ambush was the latest in a series of attacks demonstrating
Russian forces' vulnerability to the rebels even though they are
better-equipped and numerically superior.
</P>
<P>
   Russian ground forces entered Chechnya in late September and
have driven most rebels out of the flatlands and into the mountains
that make up the republic's southern third. The rebels are skilled
guerrilla fighters who use the rugged terrain of southern Chechnya
to their advantage, while Russian forces struggle to move their
heavy equipment in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   As the war drags on, international criticism of Russia's
offensive and alleged abuses by federal troops also continues.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has rejected the allegations, but in an apparent bow to
international pressure, the Kremlin invited the U.N. High
Commissioner for Human Rights to visit Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner, Mary Robinson, flew today to Ingushetia, a
region adjacent to Chechnya that has given shelter to most of the
250,000 refugees from the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's two-day tour of the region is expected to include a
visit Sunday to the Chernokozovo detention center in Chechnya,
where human rights groups say prisoners were routinely tortured.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is extremely important that serious allegations of human
rights violations are followed up and investigated,'' she said
after arriving in Moscow on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson visited refugee camps in Ingushetia today, where
authorities two days ago began serving hot meals for the first time
since February and began delivering bread to all officially
registered refugees in the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to international pressure, Russia has only recently
allowed international human rights officials to go to the Chechen
conflict zone.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson entered a tent at a refugee camp in the village of
Ordzhonikidzovskaya to ask about conditions there and whether it
was dangerous to return home.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is impossible to return, everyone has lost their homes,
everyone had family members killed,'' Aza Yupayeva, a refugee from
the Chechen capital Grozny, said she told Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's visit and the agreement this week to allow the Red
Cross access to detention centers in Chechnya came just days before
an April 3-4 meeting of the Council of Europe, the continent's
leading human rights watchdog, on whether to suspend Russia for
abuses in Chechnya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0849 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 08:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China National Theater Work Begins  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China began work on a futuristic and
controversial 6,200-seat national theater Saturday, 42 years after
then-Premier Zhou Enlai proposed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the titanium and glass domed building in a lake
in central Beijing is expected to take three years.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary work on the 2 million square-foot site, next to the
Great Hall of the People near Tiananmen Square, began on Saturday,
the state-run Xinhua News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The building will contain four halls -- a 2,500-seat opera hall,
a concert hall with 2,000 seats, a theater with 1,200 seats and a
smaller theater that will seat 520.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will enter through a tunnel under the lake, which will
be surrounded by grass and trees.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have argued that the monument lacks Chinese
characteristics, is too expensive and too ostentatious.
</P>
<P>
   The theater is based on a design by French architect Paul Andreu
and Beijing's prestigious Qinghua University, Xinhua said. Andreu
helped build the Grande Arche de la Defense west of Paris and the
Channel Tunnel terminal in Calais.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Zhou first proposed a national theater in 1958. A huge
hole was dug, but work stopped because of financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Xinhua did not give a price tag for the theater. But the
government's share of the cost was announced previously at $314
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 0858 </TRAILER>
