<DOCNO> APW20000401.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Protest Sale of Rover  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) -- Thousands filled the streets of this
central English city Saturday to protest German auto giant BMW's
decision to break up the loss-making Rover car group.
</P>
<P>
   The rally, part of a public campaign to save the 8,000 jobs at
Rover's main Longbridge plant in Birmingham, attracted about 40,000
people. More were expected throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders and lawmakers began gathering early, while crowds
of supporters filled the sidewalks waving banners and placards,
reading ''Betrayed,'' ''No Surrender'' and ''Save Rover. Save Us.''
</P>
<P>
   BMW announced its plan earlier this month to sell Rover to a
group of British venture capitalists, Alchemy. The group has no
experience with auto-making, and has acknowledged that job losses
are inevitable as the plant becomes a niche producer of sports cars
under the name MG Car Co. Ambitiously, Alchemy hopes to post a
profit within three years and sell the company within seven.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders fear that Rover will be allowed to die and
thousands of jobs will go. They have been trying desperately to
find another buyer for the car group, which lost $3.2 million a day
last year, but there has been little interest.
</P>
<P>
   ''The job losses that will result from the breakup of Rover are
a catastrophe for the whole British economy but worse for the West
Midlands'' where the main plant is located, said Roger Lyons,
general secretary of the Manufacturing Science and Finance union.
</P>
<P>
   ''The message we are sending back to BMW is that their conduct
will not be tolerated by the British people,'' said Duncan Simpson,
a union negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the breakup, BMW will sell the popular Land Rover
brand of off-road vehicles to Dearborn, Mich,-based Ford Motor Co.
for $2.9 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
