<HEADLINE> G8 Education Summit Opens in Japan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Education ministers from the Group of Eight
countries gathered in Tokyo Saturday to open their first education
summit.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-day meeting, the ministers and representatives
from various international organizations will discuss international
exchanges in education and ways to deal with globalization and
information technology, officials from the Japanese Education
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the G-8 ministers, officials from the European
Union, the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
and U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization are at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   They are expected to agree to double the number of exchange
students, teachers and researchers over the next 10 years, Kyodo
News agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening address, Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi wished
success for the group's first education summit ''despite their
countries facing different problems on education,'' Kyodo quoted
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   G-8 members are Japan, the United States, Britain, Germany,
France, Italy, Canada and Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
