<HEADLINE> 4 Egyptian Journalists Face Fines  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Four Egyptian journalists were convicted in
a retrial Saturday of libeling the deputy prime minister, a
decision that included heavy fines for all four and prison terms
for three.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists of the Islamic-oriented newspaper Al-Shaab were
convicted of libeling Deputy Prime Minister Youssef Waly in a
series of articles that had accused him of trying to ruin Egypt's
agricultural sector by cooperating with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Cairo Criminal Court sentenced editor-in-chief Magdi Hussein
and reporter Salah Bdeiwi to two years in prison and cartoonist
Essam Hanafi to one year in prison. The three, plus reporter Adel
Hussein were also fined $5,800 apiece and ordered to pay $145
apiece to Waly in compensation, court officials said on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The four were convicted in August and three of them had served
part of their jail terms by December when an appeals court revoked
their sentences and ordered a retrial. The appeals court found that
the lower court judge had not allowed them enough time to defend
themselves and had rejected their demand for Waly to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The time that the three journalists have already served in
prison will be deducted from their new sentences.
</P>
</TEXT>
