<HEADLINE> Poland Party Says it Owns Slogan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- A Polish political party said Saturday it
has exclusive rights to promote its candidate with the ''President
2000'' slogan -- and will sue anybody else who uses it in this
year's race.
</P>
<P>
   Stanislaw Michalkiewicz, one of the leaders of the rightist Unia
Polityki Realnej, or Union for Real Policy, said the party filed
for the trademark last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has not been registered yet, nevertheless it already
entitles us to exclusive use,'' Michalkiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Union, a staunch advocate of radical free market reforms,
did not gain any seats in the last parliamentary elections but
intends to put forward its candidate in the presidential race this
year. Janusz Korwin-Mikke, known for his sense of humor and desire
to reduce taxes to a bare minimum, has already run twice for
president without success.
</P>
<P>
   President Aleksander Kwasniewski, an ex-communist who leads
opinion polls with some 70 percent support, has said he will stand
for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Former president Lech Walesa, legendary founder of the
Solidarity movement that toppled communist rule, plans to challenge
Kwasniewski. Another candidate is centrist Andrzej Olechowski, who
has served as finance minister and foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential elections are scheduled for fall, but no specific
date has been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
