<HEADLINE> Foreign Workers Plan Criticized  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- Criticism intensified Saturday over
a controversial campaign slogan against bringing foreign workers to
help Germany's high-tech industry, with church and business leaders
condemning the Christian Democrats' tactics in a state election.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Ruettgers, the gubernatorial candidate for the
conservatives in North Rhine-Westphalia state, has criticized a
plan by Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder to offer work permits to
20,000 computer specialists to ease what German businesses complain
is a serious shortfall of qualified workers.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives insist that Germany must curb an influx of
immigrants, especially considering its own 11 percent unemployment
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Ruettgers has turned the plan into a campaign issue, attacking
it with the slogan ''Kinder statt Inder,'' or ''children instead of
Indians.'' He has also said the party would be putting up posters
and sending out 100,000 postcards with the motto ''more training
instead of more immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the head of Germany's Lutheran Church, Manfred
Kock, called for an immigration policy that also considers the
human side of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''The connection between an election battle and such a
foreigner-hostile, populistic campaign is unspeakable and should
not happen,'' Kock said.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Association of German Industries, Hans-Olaf
Henkel, called on voters that receive the campaign postcards to
throw them in the trash.
</P>
<P>
   ''Germany cannot afford this kind of provincialism,'' Henkel
told the Westdeutsche Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Friedman, a vice president of the Central Council of Jews
in Germany and also a Christian Democrat party member, told the
Berliner Zeitung the Ruettger campaign was ''counter-productive and
archaic.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Christian Democratic Secretary-General Angela Merkel, to
be appointed the party's head at a convention this month, defended
the campaign. She said the goal of the slogan was to spur more
discussion about immigration -- and not to misuse the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need a European solution,'' she said at a state party
meeting in Saxony-Anhalt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the number of neo-Nazis in Germany is continuing to
rise, according to a report in the mass-circulation Bild newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a government report to be released next week, Bild said
that there was an 11 percent increase to about 53,600 members of
114 known far-right groups. The number of those believed to be
capable of violence rose 9 percent to about 8,200 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
