<HEADLINE> Rwandans Mourn Genocide Victims  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Rwanda began a week of mourning Saturday,
six years after a 90-day frenzy of killing and brutality that left
more than half a million people dead and tore apart this Central
African nation.
</P>
<P>
   State-run Radio Rwanda, the only national broadcaster, called on
listeners to mark the event with public discussions and
remembrance.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500,000 minority Tutsis and politically moderate Hutus
were killed in the 1994 genocide, most slaughtered with machetes,
hoes and other makeshift weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The week of mourning, during which bars and discos were to be
closed, will culminate in a ceremony Friday -- the anniversary of
the beginning of the slaughter -- in the Kigali neighborhood of
Kicukiro, where the remains of Tutsis who were hacked to death and
buried in a mass grave will be excavated and given proper burial.
</P>
<P>
   After rebels of the Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front took power
and ended the slaughter in July 1994, the dead were buried quickly
in mass graves to avoid infection and disease, often without proper
identification or the knowledge of their relatives. A reburial
ceremony has taken place each year since 1994 in a different part
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The killings began on April 7, 1994, the day after the plane
carrying ethnic Hutu President Juvenal Habyarimana was shot down by
unidentified attackers on its approach to Kigali airport.
</P>
<P>
   The news of the president's death enraged Hutu soldiers and
militiamen, who hunted down Tutsi men, women and children and
killed them on the spot, usually with machetes. Civilians also
participated in the killings. At the time, all Rwandans carried
identification cards stating whether they were Hutu, Tutsi or Twa.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda blames the United Nations for failing to prevent or deter
the killings. As soon as the massacres started, the U.N. pulled out
most of its peacekeepers, who had been sent to Rwanda to monitor a
1993 peace agreement between Habyarimana's government and the
Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front rebels.
</P>
<P>
   In Kicukiro, at least 2,000 Tutsis sought shelter at a high
school under the protection of a small company of Belgian U.N.
peacekeepers. But the peacekeepers eventually left, saying they
could no longer offer protection. The Tutsis were left to their
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Belgian peacekeepers were slain by government soldiers on
the night of April 6 while trying to protect Prime Minister Agathe
Uwilingiyimana, a moderate Hutu who was dragged from her house and
killed by members of Habyarimana's presidential guard.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the families of the slain Belgians are expected in
Kigali on Friday to attend the ceremony, together with Belgian
Prime Minister Guy Verhofstadt and Foreign Minister Louis Michel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
