<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, Oil Industry, Help Each Other  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HOLMES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- The oil business has been good to George W.
Bush, and in 1999 the Texas governor was good to the oil business.
</P>
<P>
   The first major bill Bush signed during Texas' most recent
legislative session was a $45 million tax break for small oil and
natural gas producers. The bill's numerous, bipartisan supporters
said the help was needed to keep small producers pumping under what
then were low crude-oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are tough times for the oil and gas industry, and this
legislation says our state is committed to helping this vital
industry,'' Bush, the presumed Republican presidential nominee,
said in signing the bill last March.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with oil prices now soaring, Bush has said he is
considering endorsing suspension of a 4.3 cent-per-gallon federal
gasoline tax hike that was approved as part of President Clinton's
1993 economic recovery plan. Congressional Republicans call it the
''Gore tax,'' because the vice president cast the deciding vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led Senate already is considering suspension of
the tax increase but has put off action on a rollback bill until
this coming week. But the measure uncertain prospects in the House,
and even proponents admit a rollback would offer modest relief for
motorists at best.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the Clinton administration should be blamed for prices
averaging well over $1.50 per gallon because it squandered the
goodwill built with oil producers by his father, former President
Bush, in the Persian Gulf War and because it lacks an overall
energy policy.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Bush said he would urge Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and
Mexico to ''open the spigots'' and would remind them of the U.S.
role in the 1991 war and of its economic bailout of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of opponents to the Texas tax-break bill protested
that it provided corporate welfare to oil companies while offering
little long-term relief to the industry. They said other businesses
suffered economic downturns without eliciting similar help.
</P>
<P>
   Noting efforts to hold down spending elsewhere, Bruce Buchanan,
a political scientist at the University of Texas, said of Bush:
''He's got a tender spot for (oilmen) that's not apparent in some
other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, Bush began his business career in the West
Texas oil fields, and he has received substantial support from the
industry since entering politics in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of his fund raising by the campaign finance group
Texans for Public Justice found that $5.6 million of the $41
million Bush raised for his two gubernatorial races came from the
energy and natural resources industries.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been friendly to that sector, policy-wise, and they've
been good to him in return,'' said Craig McDonald, director of the
group. ''He rewarded them with tax breaks when they cried that they
weren't making enough money.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing Bush's presidential campaign finance reports, the
Washington-based Center for Responsive Politics ranked oil and gas
eighth among top industries giving to Bush, accounting for $1.42
million thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said there was no
connection between political contributions and Bush's support for
the 1999 tax break.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor supported the legislation to help small,
independent oil producers, oil field workers and Texas families who
depend on the oil and gas sector. (They) were in a desperate
situation last year,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear Bush feels a kinship with those in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation from Yale and the Harvard Business School, Bush
returned to Midland, Texas, where his father had entered the oil
business after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Starting as a landman, who checks deeds and mineral rights, the
younger Bush founded an exploration firm in the 1970s that put
together private partnerships for drilling ventures. He named it
Arbusto, meaning ''bush'' in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   By 1982, Arbusto was on hard times. The company had less than
$50,000 in the bank and was about $420,000 in debt. Bush changed
the name to Bush Exploration Co. and took the business public.
</P>
<P>
   The company later merged, first with Spectrum 7 Energy Corp., a
firm of Cincinnati-based investors, and later with Harken Energy,
an Irving, Texas, corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his partners got $2 million in stock in the latter
merger, and he became a consultant and director of Harken. It was
during this time that Bush's business dealings came under increased
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   One incident involved a potentially lucrative offshore drilling
project awarded by the government of Bahrain in 1990 to Harken,
even though the company had never drilled a well in water.
</P>
<P>
   The news media questioned whether the Middle Eastern country was
trying to curry favor with Bush's father, then the president. The
younger Bush has said he had nothing to do with the Bahrain deal.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Bush sold almost two-thirds of his holdings,
or $840,000 in stock, at $4 a share. A week later the company
announced a major loss, and its stock closed down about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission investigated the sale as
possible insider trading but brought no action against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he sold the shares to repay a loan he had taken to
invest in the Texas Rangers baseball team in 1989. That $600,000
investment brought him about $14.9 million when the team was sold
in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1120 </TRAILER>
