<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Koreans Battle Animal Disease  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAJU, South Korea (AP) -- The roads to the demilitarized zone
north of Seoul, South Korea are usually guarded by tank traps and
military checkpoints to ferret out possible infiltrators from rival
communist North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   This week, South Korean soldiers and farmers armed with
fumigators were fighting the spread of a new adversary:
hoof-and-mouth disease.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, soldiers flagged down vehicles traveling in and out
of this low-lying farming town 30 miles north of Seoul. Each car
and truck was directed to roll slowly across thick spongy rugs
doused with chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Weary farmers kept 24-hour guard, blocking off the entrances to
their villages and washing down each car with a chemical solution
before letting it through. A gaggle of girls returning from school
dutifully stepped on the wet rugs and cleaned the soles of their
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   A contaminated village nearby was cordoned off Saturday. Plumes
of smoke spiraled in the clear blue sky as soldiers wearing
chemical warfare outfits trundled wheelbarrows full of hay out to a
burn site, destroying it in case it had come in contact with the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a life-or-death matter for us. Our whole livelihood
depends on it,'' said cattle farmer Yoo Chong-kyu, 40.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mad cow disease, which is believed to cause a
brain-wasting ailment in humans, hoof-and-mouth disease cannot be
passed on to consumers. But it can ruin entire beef and milk cow
herds. The highly contagious virus causes fever and blisters on the
feet and mouths, sapping animals' appetites and causing weight loss
and possibly death.
</P>
<P>
   The last outbreak of hoof-and-mouth disease in Asia occurred in
Taiwan in 1997, when ranchers were forced to destroy 3.6 million
pigs -- more than 80 percent of the nation's hog population.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean scare began last week when 15 cows in Kumpa, a tiny
village surrounded by walnut tree-covered hills, collapsed with the
telltale fever and blisters. Health authorities moved in, burning
down barns and slaughtering all 105 head of cattle there.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea says it contained the disease at an early stage. But
as the United States, Japan, Australia and Taiwan moved to suspend
imports of South Korean dairy products, the government said Friday
it was willing to slaughter all 350,000 head of livestock within a
12-mile radius of the farms in Paju -- a $90 million cleanup
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The government plans to buy the meat of the slaughtered
livestock or reimburse farmers who have to sell their meat at lower
prices. The meat will be sold in domestic markets because it is not
infected, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The government took out ads telling people that the disease
cannot be transmitted to humans, and domestic consumption of beef
and pork began picking up after a sharp drop, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But farmers -- many of whom were devastated by the Asian
financial crisis and then by last year's heavy flooding -- did not
let their guard down.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have all blocked entrances to our village, except the main
gateway. We stand guard 24 hours a day so that nobody gets in
unless we clean him up,'' said Chung Hwan-shik in Kekhyun, a
community two miles north of the contaminated village.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1140 </TRAILER>
