<HEADLINE> Census Bureau's Privacy Protections  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The Census Bureau says that, by law, it cannot share
answers on
census forms with the Internal Revenue Service, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, or any other government agency.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Also:
</P>
<P>
   --Census Bureau workers must pass security and employment
reference checks. They cannot currently work as tax collector,
assessors or law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   --Agency workers are sworn to secrecy. The face a $5,000 fine and
a five-year prison term if the give out any information they see on
a form.
</P>
<P>
   --The Census Bureau protects information on forms with security
measures including electronic barriers, scrambling devices and
dedicated lines. Answers on your form are combined with others to
produce the statistical summaries that are published.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Census Bureau
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1151 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
