<DOCNO> APW20000401.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reasons Behind Census Questions  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Selected questions on census 2000 forms, and some of
the
rationale the Census Bureau gives for asking them. The last three
questions are found only on the 53-question long form, sent to one
in six of the country's 115 million households:
WHAT IS THIS PERSON'S RACE?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal Uses:
</P>
<P>
   --Needed to asses racial disparities in health and environmental
risks.
</P>
<P>
   --Used under the Voting Rights Act to identify minority language
groups that require voting materials in their own language.
</P>
<P>
   --Used under the Civil Rights Act to assess fairness of
employment practices.
</P>
<P>
   Community Impact:
</P>
<P>
   --Needed under the Public Health Service Act as a key factor in
identifying segments of the population who may not be receiving
needed medical services.
</P>
<P>
   --Required by states to meet legislative redistricting
requirement by knowing the racial make-up of the voting age
population.
WHAT WAS THIS PERSON'S TOTAL INCOME IN 1999? (and other
income-related questions.)
</P>
<P>
   Federal Uses:
</P>
<P>
   --Provides vital measure of general economic circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   --Used to determine poverty status, and the need for various
types of assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Community Impact:
</P>
<P>
   --Guides funding for social services distributed to local
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   --Identifies local areas eligible for grants to run job training
and other employment programs.
</P>
<P>
   --Used to allocate funds to areas requiring housing assistance
and home energy aid.
HOW MANY MINUTES DID IT USUALLY TAKE THIS PERSON TO GET FROM HOME
TO WORK LAST WEEK? (and other questions related to commuting to
work.)
</P>
<P>
   Federal Uses:
</P>
<P>
   --Needed to plan highway improvements, develop public
transportation services, design programs to ease traffic problems,
conserve energy, and reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
   --Needed to develop standards to reduce work-related vehicle
trips and increase passenger occupancy during peak periods of
travel.
</P>
<P>
   Community Impact:
</P>
<P>
   --Used by metropolitan planning organizations to manage traffic
congestion and develop strategies to mitigate the congestion such
as carpooling programs and flexible work schedules.
</P>
<P>
   --Needed to plan emergency services in areas of high
concentrations of employment.
</P>
<P>
   --Needed by public transit agencies to plan transit investments,
identify areas needing better transit services, determine the most
efficient routes, and plan services for disabled persons.
DO YOU HAVE COMPLETE PLUMBING FACILITIES IN THIS HOUSE, APARTMENT,
OR MOBILE HOME; THAT IS, 1) HOT AND COLD PIPED WATER, 2) A FLUSH
TOILET, and 3) A BATHTUB OR SHOWER?
</P>
<P>
   Federal uses:
</P>
<P>
   --Needed by federal agencies to identify areas eligible for
public assistance programs and rehabilitation loans.
</P>
<P>
   --Used by public health officials to locate areas in danger of
ground water contamination and waterborne diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Community impact:
</P>
<P>
   --Used by state and local agencies, along with the Department of
Agriculture, to identify poor quality housing.
</P>
<P>
   --Used to allocate Section 8 and other Federal housing subsidies
to local government which help Americans afford decent, safe, and
sanitary housing.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Census Bureau
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1151 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Pass Time at Watch Fair  </HEADLINE>
By CLARE NULLIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- The atmosphere oozes unashamed, unadulterated
luxury as top watchmakers from around the world display their
glory, tantalized by the prospect of lucrative orders improving
already strong sales.
</P>
<P>
   Soft carpets, subtle lighting and sweet talk coddle visitors to
the weeklong exhibition as they indulge in a feast of
diamond-studded beauty, state-of-the-art precision and watches with
price tags of up to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Only elite jewelry retailers were invited to the exhibition,
which features top-of-the-line models from 17 luxury manufacturers.
There is none of the high-pressure bustle that usually accompanies
trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
   Money talks. Wealth whispers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't just come here to drink champagne, we come here to
dialogue with each other, to place orders, to make Swiss
watchmaking work,'' said Franco Cologni, president of the
International Salon of Haute Horlogerie.
</P>
<P>
   But one Swiss watchmaker was noticeably absent: Swatch -- the
world's biggest watch company with $2.2 billion in 1999 revenue and
maker of what is said to be the most successful watch of all time --
had nothing on display.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Hayek, a marketing wizard whose plastic Swatch saved the
ailing Swiss industry in the 1980s, refused to stage an exhibit,
accusing organizers of elitism and setting difficult entry
conditions for Swiss companies -- while at the same time allowing in
foreign companies like London-based Alfred Dunhill.
</P>
<P>
   Other exhibitors -- including renowned names such as Audemars
Piguet, Baume and Mercier and Breguet -- had no such reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're here with the top brands and we can meet up with the
world's top jewelers in the city which is the original home of top
watches,'' said Klaus-Juergen Schneider of Mont Blanc. ''It's THE
event of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider and other company executives attending the event,
which ends Tuesday, hope to woo customers from the Far East, the
United States and Brazil. Contacts made and contracts signed in
Geneva will account for at least 50 percent of annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   The mood is equally upbeat on the stand of Geneva watchmaker
Piaget, whose range includes the ''Ladies Butterfly'' -- a watch
whose case is in an elaborate butterfly design comprising 222
diamonds, six rubies, nine pink sapphires and mother of pearl. All
for just $108,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also on display: the glittering ''Lady Kalla'' watch with a
diamond studded bracelet. The price is $287,000.
</P>
<P>
   After years of fretting about foreign competition and economic
recession, the Swiss watch industry is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Exports of watches and watch parts rose to a record $5.4 billion
last year, up 7 percent from 1998. Sales of luxury watches -- those
that cost more than $300 -- soared 12 percent to $3.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The increase was largely due to a 14 percent rise in sales to
the biggest customer, the United States, which last year bought
$900 million worth of Swiss watches. Bumper orders also came from
Asia -- Hong Kong and Japan are the second and third biggest
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Hayek said the Swatch group, which owns expensive brands like
Longines and Omega, will stick to the much bigger Basel watch fair,
which is open to all comers -- until Geneva organizers change their
snobbish attitude.
</P>
<P>
   As proof that his clientele can compete with the best, he cites
the example of President Clinton, who called for an impromptu
supper at a highway rest stop after an international conference in
the Swiss Alps in January.
</P>
<P>
   ''He bought American cola, American pizza and six plastic Swatch
watches,'' said Hayek.
</P>
<P>
   ''And if you see Gianni Agnelli, the richest man in Italy, he
wears a Swatch,'' added Hayek, referring to the Fiat industrial
tycoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what you call luxury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1153 </TRAILER>
