<HEADLINE> Reno Says Only Elian's Dad Has Say  </HEADLINE>
By KIMBERLY LAMKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno appealed
to Americans on Saturday not to politicize the case of 6-year-old
Elian Gonzalez and said that the boy's father should have the right
to speak for him.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who favors returning the boy to his father in Cuba, spoke
during a discussion on international law at the University of
Virginia Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Her comments came two days after Vice President Al Gore broke
with the Clinton administration and called for keeping the boy in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is so important for all Americans to make sure we
don't politicize the issue, that we do this within the law ... that
we get it done in an orderly and calm and fair way,'' Reno said in
response to a student's question during the forum. She did not
elaborate on the point.
</P>
<P>
   She also reiterated her belief that the prerogative for
determining the future of a child Elian's age belongs first to his
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the recognition in this case is that a father must
speak for a 6-year-old, and particularly in the difficult
circumstances Elian has been in, the parent is the one that should
be speaking for him,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was rescued off the Florida coast in November after the
boat he was on sank during a voyage to reach the United States. His
mother, who was divorced from his father, died along with 10
others.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, contends the boy belongs with
him in Cuba, and the island's communist government has said
Gonzalez is willing to travel to the United States to retrieve him
from the boy's great-uncle, with whom Elian has been living in
Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
