<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Schools Making a Comeback  </HEADLINE>
By JOSHUA KUCERA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORK UNION, Va. (AP) -- Military schools, with their square
notions of crisp uniforms and strict discipline, were once as
trendy as a buzz cut.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, there were 160 of the institutions nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are just 40, but their concept -- and their
enrollment -- is making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Two new military schools are in the works, existing institutions
report rising piles of applications and even the liberal mayor of
Oakland, Calif., Jerry Brown, is supporting military-style
education as a remedy for troubled schools in his city.
</P>
<P>
   ''The discipline issue, the organizational skills that we teach,
the core values of spirituality, honesty and integrity. ... Parents
are not finding those kind of things in public schools,'' said John
Jackson, a retired Air Force lieutenant general who serves as
president of Fork Union Military Academy in central Virginia.
Applications there are up 15 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cadets at the rural school, about 50 miles west of Richmond,
attend a full day of classes, then go to marching drills, sports
practice, dinner, a two-hour study session and bed.
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledge the strict rules and remote location can chafe,
but overall they give the school high marks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's done nothing but good for me,'' said Jim Davis, 18, of
Richmond, who is taking a fifth high school year at Fork Union to
become eligible to play defensive end at Virginia Tech next year.
''I was so lazy (before), but being here, there's no time to be
lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Akers, 18, of Charleston, W.Va., said Fork Union has
boosted his grades to a B average.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not easy at all,'' he said. ''It's because you're
disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nonconformists don't do well here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the attraction for some parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Public schools have slipped a lot recently,'' said David
Morris of Bridgeport, W.Va., who has one son at Fork Union and
another who graduated. ''For one thing, they just don't have the
discipline they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Some public school districts, including Chicago and Richmond,
have turned to military education methods to improve ailing
inner-city schools. In Jerry Brown's Oakland, California Gov. Gray
Davis has proposed $1.3 million in state money to open an
Oakland-Alameda Military Institute this fall.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, conservative parents are getting more
aggressive in finding alternatives to public education.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1965, two new military high schools are
being planned: Virginia Naval Academy in northern Virginia and
Oceana Naval Air Academy on the Gulf Coast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that is due to the booming economy, which has
contributed to an increase in admissions in all boarding schools,
including military schools, said Steve Ruzicka, executive director
of the Association of Boarding Schools.
</P>
<P>
   At Fork Union, where tuition, fees and uniforms run about
$18,000 a year, about 15 percent of cadets get financial aid. A
year at other military schools can run $9,000 to $22,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   About 98 percent of Fork Union's graduates go on to college,
about 20 percent of those to service academies or private military
colleges. The school's last two valedictorians went to Harvard,
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, military school officials say, they keep bumping up
against an old stereotype: military school as a place to punish a
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are fighting as hard as we can against that outmoded
image,'' said Lewis Sorley, executive director of the Association
of Military Colleges and Schools of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While the 102-year-old Fork Union remains an all-male school,
about a third of military high schools now accept girls.
</P>
<P>
   And as Lt. Col. Jim Akers, Fork Union's admissions director, put
it: ''No one's going to spend the kind of money it takes to go to
this school to punish a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Association of Military Colleges and Schools:
http://www.amcsus.org.
</P>
<P>
   Fork Union Military Academy: http://www.forkunion.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1235 </TRAILER>
