<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton picks up union endorsements  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton was to pick up the
endorsements of two politically powerful labor unions Saturday in
her battle for the Senate against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   In Syracuse, the first lady was to be greeted by about 500
leaders of the Civil Service Employees Association, whose 265,000
members make it the state's second largest public employee union.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Saratoga Springs, Clinton was to address about 500
teachers attending the annual delegate assembly of the
40,000-member National Education Association of New York, the
state's second largest teachers' union.
</P>
<P>
   The union backing means money and volunteers for the Senate
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago when Democrat Charles Schumer unseated Republican
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, the CSEA remained neutral in the race while
the state's powerful teacher unions lined up behind the challenger.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the first lady will deliver the keynote address to
the annual convention of the New York State United Teachers Union
being held in New York City. The 430,000-member NYSUT is the
state's largest public employee union and its largest teachers'
union. It is expected to endorse Clinton later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been courting labor unions heavily as she attempts
to put together the traditional coalition of labor, minorities and
the poor that has helped other Democrats win in New York.
</P>
<P>
   This past Sunday, Clinton was in Albany to pick up the
endorsement of the Working Families Party, a labor-union backed
party founded in 1998 to help push the Democratic Party to the
left.
</P>
<P>
   ''That nomination makes our point about Mrs. Clinton being a
candidate of the far left,'' Giuliani said a day later.
</P>
<P>
   While the first lady has been lining up union support, the New
York City mayor has been beating her in fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Giuliani campaign announced it had raised $7
million during the first three months of this year. Clinton aides
said she had raised $4 million. Since the fund raising began last
year, Giuliani has raised $19 million and Clinton has collected $12
million in what is expected to become the most expensive Senate
race in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   A poll out Wednesday from Marist College's Institute for Public
Opinion had the race about even with Giuliani favored by 46 percent
of voters surveyed and Clinton backed by 43 percent of them.
</P>
<P>
   The NEA endorsement comes as no surprise. Last summer, the
national NEA gave the first lady its highest award during a
ceremony in Florida at which NEA President Bob Chase told 9,000
delegates that Clinton was ''a national treasure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
