<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another year, another late budget in New York  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- That sound you didn't hear from Albany as
this April 1st arrived wasn't from an absence of howling protest,
or gnashing of teeth from state legislators and the governor as
another fiscal year began without a new budget.
</P>
<P>
   A shrug of the shoulders makes no sound.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature and governor accepted their latest failure -- it
is the 16th straight year in New York in which the budget has been
late -- with hardly an acknowledgment that anything was even wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The days leading up to the start of the 2000-01 fiscal year were
marked by no conclusive fiscal discussions between Gov. George
Pataki and legislative leaders, no public talks over the budget in
legislative conference committees and no substantial protests about
yet another late budget.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Dollinger, a Rochester Democrat, was among
only a handful of legislators casting symbolic votes against a $2.4
billion emergency appropriations bill approved by lawmakers
Thursday before they left town for this weekend. It is designed to
cover state spending from April 1-16.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just worn down,'' Dollinger said. ''This is a process of
attrition and ... frankly, no one even talks about it any more. It
seems to me we fail the public credibility test every time we do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll last month from Siena College suggests that Dollinger is
right. Ninety percent of New Yorkers age 18 and older surveyed said
an on-time budget is either ''important'' or ''very important'' to
them and that both the governor's and the Legislature's approval
ratings go down during budget impasses.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also true that there has been no known instance of a
lawmaker getting voted out of office by constituents angry about
late budgets.
</P>
<P>
   For a second year, lawmakers will face a more tangible loss when
their $3,057-every-two-weeks paychecks will be withheld for as long
as they go past April 1 without approving a new budget.
</P>
<P>
   A late budget was inevitable this year since March 10. That's
when a deadline passed without a consensus between the Legislature
and governor on available revenues to spend in fiscal 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, some secret negotiations between the governor and
legislative leaders failed to lead to the convening of conference
committees by the Legislature to discuss details of how to spend
the $500 million to $1.3 billion -- or more -- that the Legislature
will appropriate above the $76.8 billion Pataki has proposed
spending.
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said he would not
participate in any closed-door bargaining sessions over the budget
this year, but he relented last week in hopes of getting the
conference committee process jump started. It didn't produce a
deal, but Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said he thought an
agreement could be reached this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's possible,'' he said. ''I think probable.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's budget-making process was also being called as
secretive and exclusionary as any in memory.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very much underground,'' state Comptroller H. Carl
McCall said. ''Nobody seems to know. The members are always the
last to know. .. They are all in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Fortuna, president of the New York City-based Citizens
Budget Commission, said the ''quality of the process does seem to
be deteriorating in the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Not only have the budgets gotten later but consensus seems
more and more elusive for state leaders,'' Fortuna said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Roy Goodman, a Manhattan Republican, joked that this
year's budget-making process has been ''progressive
retrogression.''
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Steven Sanders, a Manhattan Democrat, said he
was sticking by a prediction he first made in 1999 -- that the
budget would be adopted in a month beginning with the letter ''a.''
Unfortunately, last year that month wasn't April but August, and
the Aug. 4 adoption missed breaking by a matter of hours the
all-time record for a late budget in New York. The previous record
was set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Chief disagreements in the 2000-01 budget are over tax cuts,
spending on transportation facilities and funding of some education
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno, who has been feuding with his fellow Republican Pataki,
said last week his relationship with the governor was not a factor
in delaying a new budget. But Democrats in the Assembly missed few
opportunities in March to allude to the Bruno-Pataki tiff and
suggest it would hinder the high-level budget negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is as crazed as it can get,'' Assemblyman Richard Brodsky,
D-Westchester, said. ''We are holding the coats of Sen. Bruno and
Gov. Pataki and expect to do a three-way agreement when the winner
and the loser of that particular battle emerges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-01-00 1303 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
