<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State to try to finish 'holy grail' of an elderly health study  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A state agency says it is not abandoning a
study about the health of New York senior citizens who were
enrolled in programs which provided them with nutritious meals.
</P>
<P>
   The state Office for the Aging will run out of the $70,000
budgeted for the program at the end of this month. Officials will
meet soon with experts at the State University of New York at
Albany to determine if that school can complete the study, or
recommend the best way it be finished, according to Frank
DeMarinis, deputy director of local program operations at the aging
office.
</P>
<P>
   DeMarinis and advocates for the elderly say the study of the
health of about 200 seniors in New York is the only one of its kind
ever conducted in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   They say it will provide the first scientific look at the
effects of nutrition on older people, and offer some idea about how
much less care -- hospitalization, doctors' visits, nursing home
stays -- elderly people getting proper food needed compared with
those not getting the right nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no study like this in the country,'' said Greg Olsen
of the Statewide Senior Action Council. ''This is the state of the
art. This is the holy grail to show what we've all been saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen said the study will show that it is not only morally right
for proper food to be available for older people who cannot afford
it, but also that it makes economic sense because of lower health
care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen estimated it would take another $50,000 or so for the
study to be completed by having the data analyzed by researchers
expert at reviewing medical and statistical information.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything is basically done,'' Olsen said. ''It needs to be
analyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMarinis said how much his office needs to complete the study,
and where the agency will try to find the money, hinges on what the
SUNY-Albany experts say.
</P>
<P>
   At a state Assembly hearing late last month in Montgomery County
on rural hunger, Assemblyman Paul Tonko said the prospect of the
study being abandoned was ''very tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not like investing $70,000,'' Tonko said. ''That's like
throwing it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen responded, ''We're talking about an almost $80 billion
budget. I don't think it would be all that difficult to find
$50,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the state's new fiscal year is expected to total
about $78 million when finally enacted by the governor and
Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-01-00 1304 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0102 </DOCNO>
