<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A History of Mount Usu  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some background on Mount Usu, in northern Japan,
which has come
back to life after more than two decades of silence:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   THE VOLCANO: Mount Usu is one of 86 active volcanoes in Japan.
It is known to have erupted eight times in the past 300 years. Its
last eruption began in 1977 and continued into the following year,
starting mudslides that killed at least two people. An eruption in
1822 killed 50 people.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   THE TOWNS: Several towns lie at the base of the volcano, many
depending on volcanic hot springs and the scenic Lake Toya to draw
tourists. Date, the largest city near Usu, has a population of
35,656. Altogether, about 51,000 people live near the volcano.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   THE THREATS: Past eruptions of Usu have generally not included
quantities of glowing red lava running down its slopes, as seen in
Hawaii. Here, eruptions have been accompanied by pyroclastic flows
-- a roiling mixture of superheated gas, rock and ash that can race
down the mountain at speeds of 60 mph or more. Experts worry that
the eruptions could melt the blanket of snow on Usu, starting
landslides.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LAST MAJOR ERUPTION: The most recent volcanic eruption in Japan
that led to deaths was at Mount Unzen, in southern Japan, which
rumbled to life in 1990 after 200 years of dormancy. Some 43 people
died on Unzen, many of them journalists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
