<HEADLINE> Timeline of Mount Usu Eruption  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Key events in the volcanic eruptions from Japan's
Mount Usu:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   March 28: Authorities issue volcano warning after tremors are
recorded under the Mount Usu volcano on Japan's northernmost main
island of Hokkaido. Residents begin evacuating.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   March 29: Local meteorological observatory says an eruption is
expected within days. Three towns at the base of the volcano, with
a total population of 51,000, order residents to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   March 30: Officials widen the danger zone and issue new
evacuation order. About 10,000 people flee to rescue centers and
homes of friends or relatives. Cracks over 100 yards long open on
the western side of the volcano and strong tremors continue.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   March 31: Mount Usu erupts, sending a billowing column of molten
rock and gray-blue ash into the air. Thousands of coast guard,
military and police are dispatched for rescue operations. Evacuees
bed down for a third night in school gymnasiums and community
centers. Disaster officials warn that volcanic activity could
continue for months.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   April 1: The volcano erupts again in a blast that creates a new
crater in the mountain. Two more eruptions follow. Authorities
widen the danger zone again, bringing the number of evacuees to
more than 15,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
