<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Brazil Cops Held in Drug Probe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A congressional narcotics
investigation has led to the arrests of 10 Brazilian policemen
accused of links to drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Rio de Janeiro State Security chief Josias Quintal ordered four
police detectives arrested after they testified before a
congressional panel in Rio on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The four were accused of extorting money from Brazil's
most-wanted drug trafficker, known as Fernandinho Beira-Mar. The
other six officers arrested were federal police agents accused of
helping drug trafficker Ademir Cavalline escape from police
headquarters in December.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, warrants were issued for three other officers and
the panel subpoenaed the bank, tax and telephone records of seven
more.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's investigation, which began last year, has led to the
arrest of more than 120 suspects, including judges, businessmen and
police officers. Brazilians have dubbed the investigators ''The
Untouchables'' -- a reference to the group of U.S. federal agents
under Eliot Ness who smashed Al Capone's liquor operations during
Prohibition.
</P>
</TEXT>
