<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Criminals Await Deportation  </HEADLINE>
By BEN FOX, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL CENTRO, Calif. (AP) -- Hoang Duc Nguyen's 10-month prison
sentence ended five months ago, but he is still behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law says the 30-year-old immigrant must be deported, but
the country he fled as a child refugee won't take him back.
</P>
<P>
   That's left Nguyen in a legal no man's land, and he isn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 3,400 immigrants with criminal records are in
similar holding patterns at Immigration and Naturalization Service
detention centers and jails across the United States. Some have
waited four years for authorities to decide what to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want to get out of this place,'' Nguyen, who was born
in Vietnam, said as he sat at a visitor's booth at the INS
detention center in El Centro, about 120 miles east of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 of the 500 prisoners at the center cannot be returned
to their countries. Instead, they're left living in a
barracks-style jail in the desert that was designed to hold illegal
migrant workers for a few days, not years.
</P>
<P>
   The INS already is struggling with a record number of prisoners.
Tougher immigrations laws have more than doubled the numbers to
18,000 since 1996, when Congress eliminated a requirement that the
INS release anyone who couldn't be deported within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Those immigrants who are stuck here, like Nguyen, come from a
handful of countries, including Cuba, Laos and Vietnam, that won't
take them back.
</P>
<P>
   ''We keep hearing that the State Department is negotiating with
these countries to try to send some of these people back,'' said
Kim Porter, an INS assistant district director in San Diego.
''We're at their mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the chairman of a House subcommittee that
funds immigration operations blasted the INS after Justice
Department figures showed nearly 12,000 of the 35,000 immigrants
with criminal records released over the past five years committed
new crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the INS said many of the releases weren't at the
agency's discretion because the incarcerated immigrants had won
their deportation cases or because bond was allowed by immigration
and federal judges.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, INS has freed about 1,000 convicted immigrants
on bond under special review. But those awaiting review, and those
deemed too risky to release, simply must wait.
</P>
<P>
   If Nguyen had a choice, he would stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived with his family in 1979, but never completed his
citizenship application. Then, in the mid-1990s, he was convicted
twice of cocaine possession and ordered deported as a ''criminal
alien.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I came here as a kid and I don't know anything about
Vietnam,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He fought the deportation order, but as the weeks at El Centro
turned into months, he grew tired of the legal wrangling and the
boredom of confinement. The center has also become a dangerous
place, he said. Fights are common and there were two riots within
the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he gave up on his bid to stay in America. He hopes
the INS will review his case later this spring and release him on
bond to wait while officials try to reach a deportation agreement
with Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ''They could go pick him up and deport him without any
warning,'' said his lawyer, Gary Finn. ''He'll always have that
hanging over him. But he'd rather have that than stay in custody.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't know when you are going to get out or if you're
going to get out; it's psychologically traumatizing,'' said Robert
Boyle, a federal public defender in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration authorities insist they have no choice in the matter
and are simply following the will of Congress. ''INS gains
absolutely nothing by keeping people in detention longer than
necessary,'' said INS spokesman Russ Bergeron.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's budget has more than doubled with its booming
population, rising to $809 million from $366 million in 1996. This
year, officials plan to increase the agency's holding capacity by
1,000 spaces, and begin transferring 500 prisoners to the federal
Bureau of Prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials readily admit centers like the one in El Centro
are not designed to hold convicts for long periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Costa, 42, who came to the United States from Cuba
in 1980, has spent nearly 2{ years there and given up any thought
of staying in America. He has appealed to the Red Cross to help him
get home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to be involved in this anymore,'' Costa said. ''I
just want to finish it and go back to my country.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Immigration and Naturalization Service:
http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
