<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Koreans Battle Animal Disease  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAJU, South Korea (AP) -- Still struggling to contain the spread
of foot-and-mouth disease in a village north of Seoul, South Korean
officials on Saturday reported a new outbreak of the deadly
livestock illness 90 miles farther south.
</P>
<P>
   In a special announcement shortly before midnight Saturday, the
Agriculture Ministry said that ''some'' cows at Hongsong, 60 miles
south of Seoul, showed symptoms of the disease and were immediately
quarantined. Ministry officials declined to disclose further
details, saying they will make a formal announcement early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   SBS-TV, quoting farmers in Hongsong, said 40 to 50 milk cows at
two farms were found to have severe blisters in their mouths and
that government veterinarians tentatively diagnosed it as
''quasi-hoof and mouth disease.'' Authorities set up roadblocks and
prohibited the movement of all villagers and animals within six
miles of the infected farms, SBS-TV said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the distance between the two affected areas, government
officials feared that the highly contagious disease might already
have spread extensively.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mad cow disease, which is believed to cause a
brain-wasting ailment in humans, foot-and-mouth disease cannot be
passed on to consumers. But it can ruin entire beef and milk cow
herds. The highly contagious virus causes fever and blisters on the
feet and mouths, sapping animals' appetites and causing weight loss
and possibly death.
</P>
<P>
   The last outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease in Asia occurred in
Taiwan in 1997, when ranchers were forced to destroy 3.6 million
pigs -- more than 80 percent of the nation's hog population.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean scare began last week when 15 cows in a small village
near Paju, 30 miles north of Seoul, collapsed with symptoms of the
disease. Health authorities moved in, burning down barns and
slaughtering all 105 head of cattle in Kumpa village.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, soldiers set up roadblocks on all roads leading to
Paju and checked vehicles and travelers. All vehicles moving in and
out of the area were forced to roll slowly across thick spongy rugs
doused with chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Weary farmers kept 24-hour guard, blocking off the entrances to
their villages and washing down each car with a chemical solution
before letting it through. A gaggle of girls returning from school
dutifully stepped on the wet rugs and cleaned the soles of their
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The contaminated village near Paju was cordoned off Saturday.
Plumes of smoke spiraled in the clear blue sky as soldiers wearing
chemical warfare outfits trundled wheelbarrows full of hay out to a
burn site, destroying it in case it had come in contact with the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a life-or-death matter for us. Our whole livelihood
depends on it,'' said cattle farmer Yoo Chong-kyu, 40.
</P>
<P>
   As the United States, Japan, Australia and Taiwan moved to
suspend imports of South Korean dairy products, the government said
Friday it was willing to slaughter 350,000 head of livestock within
a 12-mile radius of the farms in Paju.
</P>
<P>
   The government plans to buy the meat of the slaughtered
livestock or reimburse farmers who have to sell their meat at lower
prices. The meat will be sold in domestic markets because it is not
infected, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
