<DOCNO> APW20000401.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More troubled kids need help, Whitman offers plan  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- They tried everything -- counseling, child
study teams, anger management courses.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one night, in desperation and fear, the Monmouth County
parents called the police. Their teen-age son was threatening to
kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was in a rage,'' remembers his mother ''Mary,'' who asked
that her real name not be used to protect her son's privacy. ''He
took a knife and put it to himself, so they arrested him, and they
did me a favor because then the system kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   ''We refused to let him come home,'' she adds. ''We told the
judge we were afraid of our own son.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy stayed in detention for about two months while a
psychiatric team evaluated him. The team finally decided he needed
to be in a South Jersey treatment program that is like a wilderness
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the boy is making progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's in the best place that's available out there,''
said his mother.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like an extreme step -- to call the police on your own
child. But it happens frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Parents of disturbed children often have nowhere else to turn.
Insurance coverage for mental health is quickly exhausted. Schools
and pediatricians offer little help, parents say. And the children
get sicker and sicker.
</P>
<P>
   So parents call the cops. Or they call the state Division of
Youth and Family Services, which is supposed to help abused
children but also ends up dealing with children who have severe
mental health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has to reach such a horrible point before you can find
help,'' said Bonnie, a Monmouth County parent whose teen-age
daughter tried to commit suicide twice.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with increasing pressure on state systems, Gov. Christie
Whitman now wants to help.
</P>
<P>
   She has proposed a $206 million children's initiative that is
supposed to turn the state's fragmented service system into
one-stop shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The new system will, in theory, provide the right help for each
troubled child and teen. There will be a special agency to call.
That agency will create individual treatment plans and then provide
the programs the child needs.
</P>
<P>
   Services will stretch across state departments, so kids can get
help no matter which agency they come to first. And parents will
find the support they need to cope.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tall order.
</P>
<P>
   Children are showing up with more severe mental or emotional
problems than ever before, experts say. They're violent,
confrontational and frightened. They won't listen. They refuse to
go to school. They try to kill themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it stems from child abuse. Some of it is mental illness.
But experts also say more kids are growing up alone, with parents
who are either on drugs or always at work.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're seeing more difficult children in the services that we
provide,'' says Richard Mingoia, president of Youth Consultation
Services, which has more than 70 youth treatment programs in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''It comes from feeling very much alone and abandoned in the
world,'' he explains. ''They figure, you really can't rely on
anybody, so why should you care about anybody else?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some parents say all they do is care -- and it gets them
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shirley'' has spent two years trying to get help for her
15-year-old daughter, who tried to commit suicide when she was 13.
</P>
<P>
   She has consulted pediatricians, psychiatrists, psychologists,
child study teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''The school was as in the dark as we were,'' says Shirley, who
also asked that her real name not be used. ''She needs to be in
some type of program. But there's no one to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman says her plan will eventually solve that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which is included in the proposed budget that
starts in July, the state would add $39 million in new state and
federal funding to the $167 million already spent on services for
disturbed youth. Over the next four years, funding would increase
to $280 million. Lawmakers still have to approve the spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the first year, between $8 million and $12 million would be
used to hire a company to administer the program, much like a
managed care agency, according to Laurie Facciarossa, spokeswoman
for the state Department of Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   That agency could look across all state-funded programs and
services to decide what is best for each child.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for creating county agencies that would
manage care for the most troubled children. Those county agencies
could dip into ''flexible'' pots of money that can be used for any
service a child needs, state officials promise.
</P>
<P>
   Mingoia says Whitman's proposal has some strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Pooling funding and providing a central agency to handle cases
is a good idea, he says. And, if the Whitman administration can
accomplish the difficult task of getting state departments to work
together, it would help a lot of kids.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I'm not sure there's enough money in it to really do what
they want to do,'' said Mingoia. ''You're increasing the number of
people who will be served.''
</P>
<P>
   He also questions whether it's a good idea to have a managed
care type agency handle the cases. State officials promise the
agency will have no financial incentive to deny services, as many
managed care agencies do.
</P>
<P>
   But Mingoia says that could change if the agency realizes it
lacks funds to pay for needed services.
</P>
<P>
   ''When push comes to shove, if there isn't enough money in the
system, is the managed care agency going to reduce access?'' he
wonders. ''Or are kids going to have to fail in less expensive
programs before going into more expensive ones that would work?''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, Part 2: New Jersey lacks programs for disturbed,
drug-addicted youth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-01-00 1432 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
