<DOCNO> APW20000401.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden Mayor's indictment another body blow for reeling city  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- The rolls of toilet paper in the bathroom
stalls at Camden City Hall are padlocked to prevent them from being
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is entirely unintentional in a building in which
federal authorities say just about everything else was up for
grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment last week of Mayor Milton Milan on corruption
charges linking him to the Philadelphia mob was just the latest
body blow absorbed by this already-reeling city of 87,000 that for
years has been New Jersey's poorest and most troubled. It is the
fifth-poorest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the little city that couldn't. Try as it might, this
once-proud industrial powerhouse just across the Delaware River
from Philadelphia can't shake off decades of decline that have made
its name synonymous with urban blight.
</P>
<P>
   Milan's indictment fits an all-too-familiar pattern that has
frustrated Camden residents for years: Just when it seems that good
things are starting to happen, along comes something awful to
shatter the city's fragile civic pride.
</P>
<P>
   The state chooses Camden as the spot for the New Jersey State
Aquarium, but 133 fires are set by arsonists on the night before
Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   A state-of-the-art concert hall opens on the city's waterfront,
but 60 people are murdered in the nine-square-mile city that year.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy ends a long tug-of-war by awarding the historic
battleship U.S.S. New Jersey to Camden as a floating museum, but
the mayor begs the state to take over Camden's school system, which
a judge refers to as ''a swamp of mediocrity and ...
incompetence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Camden High School basketball team wins the state
championship, but a week and a half later, the third Camden mayor
out of the last five is hauled before a judge on criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We take two steps forward and two steps back, and end up right
where we started,'' said Frank Fulbrook, president of the
Cooper-Grant Neighborhood Association and Milan's opponent in the
1997 mayoral election. ''This sure doesn't help things.''
</P>
<P>
   Milan is charged with bribery, conspiracy, extortion, money
laundering and fraud. Federal prosecutors say he received cash,
vacation trips, dinners, automobiles and home improvements from
former Philadelphia mob boss Ralph Natale and his associates in the
hope of getting city contracts in return.
</P>
<P>
   Natale has been cooperating with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Milan, 37, maintains his innocence, and calls the indictment a
politically motivated prosecution aimed at ousting the city's first
Hispanic mayor from the $75,000-a-year post. He's free on $150,000
bail.
</P>
<P>
   David Solares, who works in a pizza parlor across the street
from City Hall, grew up with Milan and doesn't believe the charges
against him are true.
</P>
<P>
   ''I went to high school with him. I know him and his wife,
Kathy, for 18 years,'' he said. ''I've seen him and his (police)
officers out in the streets bringing in drug dealers. Since he
became mayor, I haven't seen drugs as much in this city. Before,
you'd see (dealers) on the corners. If they take him out of office,
drugs will come back worse, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Milan's name repeatedly surfaced in the trial of two men,
Jose Rivera, his childhood pal, and Luis ''Tun Tun'' Figueroa, who
were convicted of running the city's largest cocaine ring ever.
Five convicted dealers testified that Milan sold $20 bags of
cocaine and purchased the drug by the kilo before becoming mayor.
</P>
<P>
   That has resident Sharon Taylor furious.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he belongs in jail, for sure,'' she said. ''If they
don't do something about him, kids that are out there selling drugs
will think, 'Hey, I can deal drugs and then become mayor, and I'll
be set for life.' I don't want my kids thinking like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble has been Camden's constant companion for decades;
indeed, the official history of Camden on the city's web site ends
at around 1920. Incorporated in 1829, Camden used to be one of the
nation's mightiest industrial hubs. The first picture tubes for
television sets were made here by the Radio Corporation of America.
</P>
<P>
   Camden was known for its shipbuilding, carriage-making,
sausage-manufacturing and iron works, and it had the country's only
nickel plant in the early 1860s, providing metal to the U.S. Mint
for the manufacture of coins.
</P>
<P>
   But after World War II, industry began moving elsewhere, and
with it went a third of the city's population. Camden got steadily
poorer, and the only significant reminder of its industrial past is
the Campbell Soup Co., which still has its world headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 census figures paint a depressing portrait of Camden,
where the median income was $17,386, and the average house was
worth $31,300. More than 3,500 housing units stood vacant, and
1,400 were boarded up.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30,600 residents were classified as living below the
federal poverty level, and 56 houses were still heated by coal; 189
had no heating systems at all, and 530 lacked complete plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   State monitors oversee the city's finances and its police
department, and are close to taking control of its 34 schools. The
city has trouble collecting taxes, adopting timely municipal
budgets and staying within state-mandated debt limits, and relies
more on state financial aid -- 75 percent of its budget -- than any
other city in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS, drug addiction, homelessness and crime are serious
problems here, and the city and Camden County last year sued the
gun industry to recoup the costs of gun violence in the county,
where 30 people died from gunshot wounds in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   With such gloomy statistics, is it any wonder tobacco shop owner
Joseph Twardy is embarrassed to tell people where he lives?
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the worst reputation in the country,'' he said.
''Hell, it can't go no lower. I was in Florida and told people I
was from Camden, and they said, 'You can't walk the streets there;
you'll get killed.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Twardy campaigned for Milan in 1997, but now regrets his former
support. After Milan's predecessor, Arnold Webster, pleaded guilty
to illegally paying himself $20,000 in school district funds after
he stopped working as superintendent and became mayor, Twardy
thought Milan would be a reformer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought a new broom sweeps clean,'' he said. ''But he swept
City Hall clean into his own pocket. We go from bad to worse
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Camden Mayor, Angelo Errichetti, who served from 1973 to
1981, spent 32 months in jail following his conviction in the
Abscam scandal. He accepted a $50,000 bribe from an undercover
F.B.I. agent.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Douglass owns a hot dog stand on Market Street, a block from
City Hall, and dreams of succeeding in Camden.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of opportunity in Camden,'' he said. ''My
partner and I just got another hot dog cart, and eventually I'd
like to open up a restaurant and maybe a billiards hall here.
</P>
<P>
   ''But things are up in the air right now,'' he said. ''Camden's
going to be at a standstill for the next three to five years. We're
going to be idle, just trying to clean up this mess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
