<BODY>
<HEADLINE> War Vets Battle Zimbabwe Protesters  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HARTNACK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Long-simmering political tensions
erupted into violence Saturday when veterans of Zimbabwe's
independence war attacked protesters opposed to President Robert
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   The attack in downtown Harare came as Mugabe struggles to retain
his 20-year hold on power. Opposition against Mugabe has grown amid
recent illegal takeovers of white-owned farms, economic
mismanagement, shortages and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Police first tried to prevent the legal demonstration and then
initially stood by as the 3,500 protesters were bloodied with
whips, clubs, rocks and bricks. It wasn't until late Saturday that
calm returned to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Some 300 veterans of the bush war that led to Zimbabwe's
independence from Britain in 1980 appeared to single out whites
among the protesters. An elderly white couple was battered to the
ground and then kicked while police stood by.
</P>
<P>
   In London, British foreign office minister Peter Hain denounced
the ''thuggery orchestrated from on high.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 15 people were badly hurt in the attack by the
pro-Mugabe war veterans, said Brian Kagoro, a spokesman for the
National Constitutional Assembly, which organized the protest
march. Hospital officials said one elderly man was in serious
condition.
</P>
<P>
   ''I put the blame squarely on the police for what happened,''
said businessman Richard Calder, who was cut and bruised. ''We were
attacked by these so-called war heroes while the police did nothing
to control the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was called to protest the takeover of more
than 700 white-owned farms by squatters led by black war veterans.
Opposition leaders say Mugabe is refusing to have his security
forces obey a court order for the squatters' eviction because he
wants to gain popular support ahead of parliamentary elections,
which could be called in May.
</P>
<P>
   Police brandishing batons, shields and riot guns -- their
greatest show of force since eight people were killed in food riots
in 1998 -- ringed the capital with roadblocks and tried to prevent
demonstrators from gathering by turning back vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   An unidentified senior policeman snatched a judge's order that
authorized the protest march from a demonstrator and threw it onto
the pavement. Two National Constitutional Assembly leaders --
architect Michael Pearce and journalist Grace Kwinjeh -- were
detained when they complained about the policeman's actions.
</P>
<P>
   After initially standing by, police fired tear gas at the mixed
group of demonstrators and war veterans in central Harare's African
Unity Square as air force helicopters swooped over the city.
</P>
<P>
   None of the ex-guerrillas was reported arrested. State media
claimed the protesters sparked the clash when they moved toward the
headquarters of the ruling ZANU-PF party, which ''provoked the war
veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   But witnesses said the ex-guerrillas clearly were the aggressors
and that the trouble started a mile from the party headquarters.
Hain, the British official, said he would raise the matter
personally with Mugabe at a summit of African and European leaders
due to start Monday in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe's second-largest city, Bulawayo, another protest
march with 4,000 demonstrators proceeded peacefully Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
