<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
First Lady at Odds With Gore on Elian
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton today opposed Congressional
action to make Elian Gonzalez a resident of this country, putting her at odds
with Vice President Al Gore. ''Hillary Clinton knows that we must take politics
out of this decision,'' said Clinton Senate campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson.
''Elian's future should be determined as quickly as possible through the
appropriate, ongoing legal process.'' Clinton's position on Elian also put her
at odds with New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. Giuliani, who maintains that
the boy should be granted U.S. citizenship and that any custody issues should be
handled in family court.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Urges Census Compliance
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton urged Americans today to make their
presence felt by completing this year's census forms completely. ''Those who
suggest that filling out your census form isn't essential are plainly wrong,''
Clinton said in his weekly radio address. ''An inaccurate census distorts our
understanding of a community's needs.'' Today is Census Day, April 1, the
once-in-a-decade day on which Americans are asked to tell the government who and
where they are. Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., chairman of the House Republican
Conference, said Republicans share the goal of a full and accurate census count,
but ''millions of Americans'' have concerns about privacy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Archer Pushes Taxpayer Privacy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Broad new taxpayer rights legislation will begin moving in
the House next week to protect sensitive tax information from computer hackers
and give people breaks on IRS interest and penalties, a top Republican lawmaker
said today. In the weekly Republican radio address, Rep. Bill Archer, chairman
of the tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee, also announced that the
committee plans three days of hearings, beginning April 11, to examine proposals
to replace the current tax code with a national sales tax, a flat tax or some
other system.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rwandans Mourn Genocide Victims
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Rwanda began a week of mourning today, six years after
a 90-day frenzy of killing and brutality that left more than half a million
people dead and tore apart this Central African nation. State-run Radio Rwanda,
the only national broadcaster, called on listeners to mark the event with public
discussions and remembrance. More than 500,000 minority Tutsis and politically
moderate Hutus were killed in the 1994 genocide, most slaughtered with machetes,
hoes and other makeshift weapons. The week of mourning will culminate in a
ceremony Friday -- the anniversary of the beginning of the slaughter.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Saudis Will Let UN Observe Courts
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Responding to allegations that Saudi police
torture detainees and that defendants are convicted in secret trials, Saudi
Arabia has offered to allow the United Nations to observe its justice system, a
Foreign Ministry official said today. The official said the United Nation's
special rapporteur on the independence of judges and lawyers, Param Cumaraswamy,
has been invited here to see how the country's courts operate. Amnesty
International released a report on Saudi Arabia this week, saying it had
documented patterns of systematic human rights violations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chirac Wants More French Films in US
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The United States should do what it can to make French films
more accessible to the American public, President Jacques Chirac said today at a
reception of the 15th Paris Film Festival. Chirac said that European films
account for only a small share of movies shown in the United States, while U.S.
movies in Europe account for more than 60 percent of what is shown in theaters
and on television. The gathering at the presidential Elysee Palace included
American actress Faye Dunaway.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Keep Knight on the Job
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A poll shows that more than half of Indiana residents
feel University of Indiana basketball coach Bob Knight should keep his job. The
survey, sponsored by The Indianapolis Star and Indianapolis television station
WTHR, was produced by the Indiana University Center for Survey Research. Poll
respondents were asked about claims by former Indiana player Neil Reed that
Knight choked him a practice several years ago. The poll showed 55.5 percent
think Knight should continue as coach, and 38.9 percent said he should not. But
more than 44.5 percent feel the school should continue its current
investigation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN
</SUBHEAD>
