<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Westfield cop hits a homer in lifelong dream tryout  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEWATER, N.J. (AP) -- As lifelong dreams go, Ed Belford's was
pretty tame. Oh sure, he's envisioned himself as a pro baseball
player under the lights on a hot summer night with thousands of
fans in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   But his dream wasn't to hit the home run to win the World Series
in his last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted to be out there playing shortstop, having a
ground ball hit to me with one out and one on in the ninth inning,
start a double-play and send everyone home happy,'' said the
Fanwood resident, who's a police officer in nearby Westfield.
</P>
<P>
   And so Saturday, after decades of wondering what might have
been, Belford, at 42, took the field at Somerset Ballpark with
about 100 hopefuls, most of them half his age. Each was trying to
win a walk-on job with the minor league Somerset Patriots of the
independent Atlantic League. The league's Newark Bears also held
open tryouts Saturday, and the Atlantic City Surf will do so on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Three years away from retiring from the police force and with a
15-year-old son playing high school baseball, Belford was better
suited to be a coach than a player. But he said he had to at least
try.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always wanted to try out for a pro team,'' he said. ''I
haven't played since college, and my son is playing now, and I
always tell him to follow his dreams. Well, it's time I started
practicing what I preached.''
</P>
<P>
   He put his chances of making the team at ''zero.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Tomorrow, I'll be raking leaves in my back yard,'' he said.
''But today I'm a baseball player. And it's a lot of fun out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   After fielding a few grounders and taking dozens of throws from
erratic young outfielders, Belford shocked the stadium by being the
first one to blast a home run out of the ballpark, a shot that
cleared the left-field wall a good 320 to 330 feet from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The other tryouts cheered for him, and for just a moment,
42-year-old Ed Belford was a baseball hero.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots general manager Dave Gasaway admitted the tryouts faced
long odds to win a contract with the team. And manager Sparky Lyle
noted the team can still select players from other teams in the
upcoming draft, making it even more difficult for a walk-on to
stick with the team.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Jay Laub did just that, impressing the Pats
enough at an open tryout to earn a contract with the team. He hit
.239 in 37 games with Somerset before being traded to the Nashua
Pride in New Hampshire, where he finished the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of guys who sit in bars or in front of TVs and
say, 'Oh, I could do that,' '' Gasaway said. ''But these are the
guys who actually come out and do it, and I give them all the
credit in the world for putting their money where their mouth is.''
</P>
<P>
   One player who appeared to have a decent shot was 22-year-old
Adrian Acevedo of Orlando, Fla., who flew up on Thursday to try
out. He was drafted out of college by the Chicago White Sox in the
16th round of the 1997 draft, but never signed with the team. A
.350 hitter in two years of junior college in Miami and two at
North Carolina State, he caught Lyle's eye by running the
60-yard-dash in 6.6 seconds and making several strong throws from
deep in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Gasaway was negotiating with Acevedo late Saturday and hoped to
have him signed to a contract by Tuesday, barring any last-minute
snags.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just trying to continue my career any way possible,''
Acevedo said before the contract was offered. ''I know I can still
play, and I know there's a place somewhere for me to play. I just
have to find it. I'm going to keep playing baseball until somebody
kicks me off the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-01-00 1610 </TRAILER>
