<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Gov. To Use $5B For Transit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Gov. Gray Davis is poised to unveil a
$5 billion plan to help solve the state's traffic woes, the San
Francisco Chronicle reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan would use $2.8 billion in state funds and
$2.2 billion in bonds, which would need voter approval. The state's
commitment would be supplemented by $10 billion in federal and
local funds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's money, $4.5 billion, would go to
construction projects, while the rest would fund rehabilitation and
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Davis declined to comment on the plan, which was
expected to be announced Wednesday in Los Angeles and Thursday in
the San Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm excited the governor is coming our way by engaging in a
pay-as-you-go plan instead of raising taxes, but we need to keep in
mind this is throwing a nickel at a problem that costs a dollar,''
Assembly Republican leader Scott Baugh of Huntington Beach told the
Chronicle. ''We need a long-term strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   One major project in the proposal is the extension of Bay Area
Rapid Transit, or BART, to San Jose. Davis' plan would lend seed
money to the $4 billion project. BART currently serves San
Francisco and the eastern San Francisco Bay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
