<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton at odds with Al Gore  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton on Saturday opposed
Congressional action to make Elian Gonzalez a resident of this
country, putting her at odds with Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Clinton knows that we must take politics out of this
decision,'' said Clinton Senate campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson.
''Elian's future should be determined as quickly as possible
through the appropriate, ongoing legal process.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was upstate Saturday to pick up the endorsements of two
politically powerful labor unions -- the Civil Service Employees
Association and the National Education Association of New York -- in
her Senate race against Republican New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee, urged
Congress last week to pass a law that would grant permanent
resident status to 6-year-old Elian, his father, stepmother, half
brother, grandmothers and grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton remains opposed to the measure.
</P>
<P>
   At an appearance in Syracuse, the first lady dodged questions
about her position and whether she felt Gore, as well as Giuliani,
was politicizing the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I put out a statement on that ... That's all I'm going to say
about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, will come to the United
States as soon as he is assured that he will be given custody of
his son, said his lawyer, Gregory Craig. The lawyer said he also
will seek permission for the boy's classmates, teacher and doctors
to travel to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's position on Elian also put her at odds with Giuliani,
who maintains that the boy should be granted U.S. citizenship and
that any custody issues should be handled in family court.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton is ducking this issue,'' said Giuliani spokesman
Bruce Teitlebaum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
