<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Warns Israel on Withdrawal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- In an apparent attempt to rattle Israeli
leaders, Lebanon's defense minister said a unilateral withdrawal
from southern Lebanon could put Syrian troops on Israel's northern
border and bring Tel Aviv within Syrian rocket range.
</P>
<P>
   Deploying Syrian troops into southern Lebanon is considered
highly unlikely, but Defense Minister Ghazi Zueiter's comments late
Friday appeared aimed at fueling fears that Israeli leaders already
have about a withdrawal without a prior agreement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Israel wants Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, to rein in
guerrillas in southern Lebanon, but has said it will withdraw by
July even without a deal. Beirut and Damascus oppose a unilateral
withdrawal and want it to take place within the context of an
overall peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   At a symposium in southern Lebanon, Zueiter raised the scenario
of Syrian troops moving into fill the void left by Israeli troops.
Some excerpts of the speech were broadcast on television Saturday,
and all were in his prepared text from which he did not diverge in
these areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''Asking Syrian forces, which are legally stationed here, to
accompany the Lebanese army to the vacated areas would be one of
the important possibilities in case of such an Israeli (troop)
redeployment,'' Zueiter said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And it would not be difficult for any normal person to
understand that this would bring Tel Aviv within the range of
Syrian missiles,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   An official statement from Zueiter late Saturday night said his
words about Syrian deployment toward the international border with
Israel were taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   The prepared text indicated Zueiter was analyzing Israeli
leaders' concerns about the possibility that with a unilateral
withdrawal Lebanon could ask Syria for help.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has had 30,000 troops in much of Lebanon since 1976. Some
are deployed in Sidon, on the coast 37 miles north of the border,
and the southern Bekaa Valley, 18 miles north of the border. Syria
has not tried to move further south.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government hasn't said what it will do if Israel
pulls out of the border zone it has occupied since 1985
unilaterally -- even whether it will send the Lebanese army to fill
the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Trade and Industry Minister Ran Cohen described
Zueiter's comments as a Lebanese-Syrian attempt to keep the border
tense while avoiding peace talks. ''This is a trick and an evasion
of responsibility by the Lebanese government in connivance with the
Syrian government,'' he said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If Israel pulls out of southern Lebanon, Syria would be deprived
of a card in its on-and-off negotiations with the Jewish state for
the return of the Golan Heights, captured by Israel in the 1967
Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has warned that attacks on it territory after a
withdrawal would be met with harsh retaliation. Israel established
the zone to prevent cross-border attacks into north Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1815 </TRAILER>
