<DOCNO> APW20000401.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Wants Ties With North Korea  </HEADLINE>
By JOJI SAKURAI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A narrow sea separates two nations that could
scarcely be more different.
</P>
<P>
   On one side, Japan, the world's second-richest country and an
engine of global capitalism. On the other, North Korea, whose
bombastic Stalinist rhetoric ill conceals a feeble economy and
near-complete isolation from the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   In talks beginning Tuesday, officials hope to narrow that gap.
How close they come could affect security throughout Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the two neighbors are scheduled to hold
five days of talks in Pyongyang, North Korea's capital, for talks
to establish diplomatic ties. Similar negotiations broke off eight
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles are formidable.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo is still angry about Pyongyang's launch of a ballistic
missile that flew over Japan in 1998 and is demanding answers about
the alleged abduction of its citizens by North Korean agents.
</P>
<P>
   The North, whose penchant for brinksmanship has always made it a
difficult negotiating partner, wants compensation for its suffering
under Japan's brutal colonial rule, from 1910 to 1945 -- a demand
Tokyo already says it will refuse.
</P>
<P>
   But while few breakthroughs are expected during the first round
of talks, there are signs that the North's desperate economic
situation might lead it to concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The North is in a weak position,'' said Toshio Miyashita, a
North Korea expert at Yamanashi Gakuin University, noting that
North Korea has been sending out diplomatic feelers to former Cold
War enemies as it seeks aid to cover drastic food shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo sees engagement with North Korea as one way to help ensure
peace in Asia. North Korea is widely seen as a sponsor of
terrorism. Its aggressive missile program and enigmatic
totalitarian regime make many consider it the biggest threat to
security in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has for years maintained a hard-line stance in dealing
with Pyongyang. In particular, Tokyo has demanded information on
citizens it accuses the North of kidnapping as a condition for
warmer ties. The abductees were allegedly taken in the 1970s and
1980s to train as North Korean spies.
</P>
<P>
   But Tokyo's stance has also softened recently.
</P>
<P>
   ''Japan feels that in order to bring about change in the North
Korean regime, it must follow a policy of engagement,'' said Masao
Okonogi, a professor of international relations at Keio University.
''The real issue for Japan is peace and stability on the Korean
Peninsula.''
</P>
<P>
   In preliminary meetings in Beijing last year, Japan promised to
resume food aid cut off after the missile launch.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say the time may be right to lure Pyongyang out of
its ideological shell.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea recently embarked on its biggest diplomatic push in
years, establishing diplomatic ties with Italy, sending envoys to
Australia and stepping up meetings with U.S. representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Okonogi said North Korean leaders seem eager to create a secure
framework for closer relations with major industrial countries in
case of a Republican victory in the U.S. presidential election.
Conservatives have stepped up criticism of what they view as the
Clinton administration's policy of appeasement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The North is really on an overall diplomatic maneuver to
prepare for a change of administration in the United States,''
Okonogi said. ''They want guarantees in case of a Republican
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   While there are promising signs, negotiations will be
complicated by the fact that neither North Korea nor Japan can
afford to appear to be making concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang relies on strident state-run media dispatches
attacking Japan, South Korea and the United States to reinforce
suspicion of the outside world among its people.
</P>
<P>
   After the ballistic missile test, Japanese public opinion swung
markedly against building warmer ties. And politicians have been
visiting the families of missing Japanese to assure them the
government will continue to push for their return.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Japanese government feels it has to take into
consideration public opinion,'' Miyashita said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1921 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Orders Inspections of Boeings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration ordered
immediate inspections Saturday of 14 Boeing 717-200 airliners to
check for potential electrical problems in altitude indicators and
make necessary modifications.
</P>
<P>
   The order follows reports of two instances of intermittent loss
of information on the captain and first officer's primary flight
display and integrated standby instrument system display, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, airspeed and altitude indicators remained
operational and the flights were completed without incident, it
said.
</P>
<P>
   The planes affected by the order are operated by Trans World
Airlines and Air Tran. Olympia Airlines, a Greek carrier, also
operates two 717-200s, which first entered service last year.
</P>
<P>
   Before the affected planes can fly again, the FAA said,
electrical cables must be coiled and stowed between the glareshield
and the standby display to further isolate the display from other
instruments and revise operational procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The agency estimated the work would take two hours to complete
at a cost of $120 per plane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1922 </TRAILER>
