<DOCNO> APW20000401.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two reputed gang members killed after police robbery  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two undercover narcotics officers, seconds after
they were robbed by five gang members brandishing fake handguns,
killed two of the suspects in a spray of 18 bullets on a Brooklyn
street, police said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With tensions in the city still high after the fatal March 16
shooting of an unarmed black man, police were quick to defend the
officers in this incident that occurred during a Friday night drug
operation in the Bushwick section.
</P>
<P>
   The dead suspects were identified as 19-year-old Tysheen Bourne
and 17-year-old Andre Fields, and were both black. Both pointed
realistic-looking fake weapons at the two officers before any shots
were fired, police Assistant Chief Joseph Esposito told a news
conference at Police Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects were affiliated with the Bloods street gang and had
previous arrest records, Esposito said. Bourne was out on parole
since September 1999 on a robbery charge, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Three suspects remained at large. The weapons used in the
robbery were actually simulated guns wrapped in black tape to make
them appear more genuine, Esposito said.
</P>
<P>
   The officers were part of Operation Condor, a controversial
anti-drug initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Undercover cops, although not part of that operation, were
involved in the fatal shooting of Patrick Dorismond on March 16.
The unarmed Dorismond was shot during a scuffle with an officer
looking to buy marijuana, setting off angry protests.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dorismond was the fourth unarmed black man shot by
police in the last 13 months, statistics show that police shootings
are actually down in New York. In 1991, there were 41 shootings; in
1999, there were 11.
</P>
<P>
   According to Esposito, the most recent incident began Friday
night when police arrested three marijuana dealers near Cooper
Street. The two officers, whose names were not released, were
standing on the street afterward when the five men approached them.
</P>
<P>
   ''These five individuals were out to rob someone,'' Esposito
said. ''They had the misfortune of picking out two of our
undercovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the assailants produced weapons, with one putting his
gun to an officer's head and the two others pointing their guns at
the second officer's back and chest.
</P>
<P>
   They snatched a gold necklace and a bracelet from one officer,
and a cell phone and a wallet from the other, Esposito said. When
they demanded that the first officer also surrender his wallet, he
was able to pull his gun and defend himself, Esposito said.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen shots were fired, with Bourne and Fields fatally
wounded. The three other suspects escaped, eluding a Friday night
manhunt that included a helicopter and a bloodhound.
</P>
<P>
   Two taped-wrapped fake guns were found on the street, along with
a broken gold chain and the officer's wallet. The cell phone was
recovered on the body of one of the dead men, Esposito said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the officers was a nine-year veteran, while the other had
been on the force for six years. Both had about two years'
experience in undercover work.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, the undercover operation was prompted by
calls from neighborhood residents complaining about the drug trade.
Since Jan. 1, more than 40 drug arrests have been made in the area,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   Bourne: 375 Thomas Boyland St.
</P>
<P>
   Fields: 165 Lott Ave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
