<DOCNO> APW20000401.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HSBC Bids $10.5B for French Bank  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The British banking group HSBC Holdings PLC
announced Saturday that it has made a $10.5 billion bid for Credit
Commercial de France and that the board of the French bank had
unanimously recommended the offer to its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The offer is for the purchase of all outstanding shares of the
French bank at a price of $144 per share in cash or, as an
alternative, 13 shares of HSBC for each Credit Commercial share,
valued at approximately $154 each.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC said the acquisition would give it a ''significant base for
operation in the Euro-zone,'' and bring relationships with most
major French companies.
</P>
<P>
   ING Groep of Amsterdam, with 19.05 percent of Credit
Commercial's shares, announced its support for the bid and said the
sale of its shares would produce a profit of approximately $864
million before tax.
</P>
<P>
   In December, ING, the Netherlands' largest financial services
company, offered $10.1 billion for Credit Commercial de France but
withdrew the bid after the French bank failed to embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC said the other major shareholder, Swiss Life with 15
percent of shares, has committed to accept its offer in exchange
for shares of HSBC.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC said that the aggregate value of its cash offer is
approximately $10.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Commercial's headquarters will remain in Paris ''and its
board and management will continue to direct its affairs,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Commercial has 650 branches in France, HSBC said. It is a
leading foreign bank in Brazil and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   For HSBC, the acquisition ''represents a unique opportunity to
build a platform in the Euro-zone, where we have been
underrepresented,'' said HSBC Group chairman Sir John Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Charles de Croisset, chairman of Credit Commercial, said the
transaction was ''the result of extensive and friendly discussions,
which have allowed us to reach agreement on a clear and concerted
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   HSBC expected the acquisition to be completed during the second
half of 2000, subject to necessary regulatory approvals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in a $9.8 billion merger, HSBC purchased Republic New
York Corp., parent of Republic National Bank of New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 1944 </TRAILER>
