<DOCNO> APW20000401.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Outrages Aboriginal Groups  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Aboriginal groups are threatening to
disrupt the Olympic games over a report that the Australian
government is playing down the number of Aboriginal children
forcibly placed with white families -- the so-called ''stolen
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   New South Wales' 118 Aboriginal land councils voted to march in
protest on Sept. 16, the first full day of competition in the games
in Sydney, The Sun-Herald newpaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly the Olympic Games will now be in jeopardy,'' Charles
Perkins, director of the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
Commission (ATSIC) director.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did not want to target the Games, but we have nothing to
lose now. We have racism at the highest level of government now,
destroying the relationship between the whites and the blacks,''
said Perkins, himself a ''stolen generation'' child.
</P>
<P>
   Believing that Aborigines were doomed and that absorbing the
children was the only alternative, the Australian government took
an estimated 100,000 Aboriginal children from their parents between
1910 and the 1970s. Light-skinned Aboriginal children were given to
white families for adoption. Dark-skinned children were put in
orphanages.
</P>
<P>
   Aboriginal groups have long demanded an apology for the policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph in Sydney reported Saturday that it had
obtained a high-level government document saying the widely
accepted numbers had been exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was never a generation of stolen children,'' it quoted
the document as stating.
</P>
<P>
   Aboriginal Affairs Minister John Herron confirmed that the
report was the work of his office and would become the federal
government's submission to an independent inquiry into the issue.
But he said it just summed up the government's existing policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
