<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three N.H. Justices May Be Removed  </HEADLINE>
By KATHARINE WEBSTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- A day after one state Supreme Court justice
was forced to resign, a state lawmaker said Saturday three of the
remaining four justices could face removal by the Legislature for
ethics violations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the state's judiciary has just had a tremendous train
wreck, and it's going to take us a long time to dig all the bodies
out of the wreckage,'' said Republican Rep. Paul Mirski.
</P>
<P>
   Mirski said he planned to file a bill Monday to impeach or
otherwise remove Chief Justice David Brock. Impeachable offenses
include ''bribery, corruption, malpractice or maladministration in
office.'' Judges can be removed for other offenses through a ''bill
of address.''
</P>
<P>
   Accused of criminal ethics violations, Justice Stephen Thayer
resigned Friday. In return, state Attorney General Philip
McLaughlin promised not to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   But McLaughlin issued a 25-page report that not only detailed
Thayer's transgressions but also accused the entire court of ethics
violations. He said it was an ''institutional practice'' for judges
who had excused themselves from cases to review and discuss draft
decisions in those cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''To disqualify means that a judge has no more authority (in a
case) than any other citizen,'' McLaughlin wrote in a cover letter.
''Practices to the contrary are unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Pierce Law Center professor Richard Hesse said the
revelation was extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ''To the extent it's a general practice and none of the judges
saw fit to blow the whistle on it, the whole court is tainted,''
Hesse said.
</P>
<P>
   The court's other members are Joseph Nadeau, who is too new to
have been involved; Sherman Horton; and John Broderick. Both Horton
and Broderick commented on a draft opinion in one case from which
they had disqualified themselves, McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Horton, in a telephone interview Saturday, said he could not
think of a single case that would have to be overturned. He also
said recused justices usually played only a minimal role, such as
commenting on grammar.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, justices who excused themselves because of poor
health might comment on the merits of a ruling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of us were lazy and wouldn't read them. I was one of the
lazy ones,'' Horton said. ''Others were interested in what was
going on in the court and would read them and comment, but nothing
that would violate the purpose or principle of recusal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 2004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 700 Indians Return to Chiapas  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- About 700 Indians have
returned to homes in the southern state of Chiapas that they fled
following a December 1997 massacre of 45 civilians by
pro-government paramilitaries in the village of Acteal.
</P>
<P>
   The residents -- the largest group to return since the massacre --
came home to the town of Chimix on Friday. They were persuaded to
return by government safety assurances and promises of social
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Chimix residents allied with anti-government Zapatista rebels
have not yet returned.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 people from 25 communities fled after the
massacre out of fear of more atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas staged a brief uprising in January 1994 in the
name of Indian rights and greater democracy. Peace talks have been
stalled for about four years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000401.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrests reported as World Bank/IMF protest ends  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos JCB101-103
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORHAM PARK, N.J. (AP) -- Hoisting signs reading ''More World,
Less Bank,'' about 200 people protested Saturday as officials of
the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank concluded a
three-day conference here.
</P>
<P>
   The mostly peaceful rally was marred by the arrests of several
protesters taken into custody late in the afternoon, near the close
of meetings sponsored by the two organizations and the Brookings
Institute. The rally was held in a barricaded parking lot next to
the Hamilton Park Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
   Police turned out in force to ensure organizers kept their
pledge that there would be no violence or vandalism at the rally,
organized by a coalition of grassroots groups called the New
Jersey/New York Mobilization for Global Justice. Coalition members
believe the World Bank and the IMF, charged with improving life in
developing countries, instead throw the countries into debt while
enriching corporations and degrading the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested were Nicole Anna Roskos, 27, of Madison; Jonathan
Crowell, 25, of Wayne; Samantha Gayathrilyer, 18, of Olney, Md.;
Dennis Griggs, 53, of New York; Hannah Tidman, 19, of North Canton,
Ohio; Brett Levin, 25, of Staten Island, N.Y.; and a 16-year-old
girl whose name was not released.
</P>
<P>
   All were charged with failing to disperse upon official orders,
except Levin, who was charged with trespassing on private property.
</P>
<P>
   On of the rally's organizers, Jeff Burchell of Madison,
criticized those who were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought we had an agreement that the rally would be here,
and some people thought that wasn't cool enough, so they wanted to
spark a confrontation with police,'' he told the Daily Record of
Parsippany for Sunday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Orange resident Miriam Axel-Lute, a member of the group New York
Direct Action Network, said the arrests began about 4:30 p.m. when
some protesters left the parking lot area and tried to stand along
a driveway departing conference delegates were expected to use.
Axel-Lute said police told demonstrators to clear the driveway, and
they began doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ''Apparently, the police believed they were doing so too
slowly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the coalition's promise of a peaceful protest, the rally
had been billed in advance as ''picking up where Seattle left
off,'' a reference to destructive demonstrations at the World Trade
Organization meeting there in November. It also was to be a prelude
to a projected demonstration of thousands at a World Bank/IMF
meeting April 16 and 17 in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people attending this weekend's conference are meeting
to discuss the collapse of economies in Asia and its effect on
developing countries. Bank spokesman Andrew Kircher said the bank
has noticed a rising level of awareness of the meetings in the
United States, especially since the Seattle protests.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Saturday's five-hour rally, protesters barely
outnumbered the police -- about 100 officers, including mounted
police and a SWAT team.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters included members of environmental, labor, student and
human rights groups. Dozens of activists and musicians addressed or
performed for the crowd of mostly college-aged people.
</P>
<P>
   ''The system stinks,'' the Rev. Jack Martin of Sacred Heart
Roman Catholic Church in Newark, told the crowd as he held a
handkerchief over his face. ''They say a rising tide lifts all
boats. It's been my experience it lifts all yachts.''
</P>
<P>
   Newark resident Rosanne Mazza, who said she attended the event
to support organized labor, shook her maracas vigorously as Bill
Kane, president of the New Jersey Industrial Union Council,
complained about corporate downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   The council's ''Solidarity Singers,'' performing to the tune of
''It's a Small World After All,'' sang lyrics including,
''Exploitation After All'' and ''For a Small Wage After All.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of protesters in the crowd waved signs with slogans such
as ''IMF/World Bank, Corporate Colonialism,'' ''Why Are Starving
People Selling Food?'' and ''World Bank, Criminal Loan Sharks.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the afternoon, the rally seemed more like a music
festival, with one folk singer hawking her CD to the crowd after
performing and some attendees sunbathing. Others had their own
agendas, promoting political causes from expanding legalized
gambling to freeing Mumia Abu Jamal, a former journalist on
Pennsylvania's death row for the killing of a Philadelphia police
officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
