<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft-U.S. Gov't Talks Crumble
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Despite assertions by Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates that his
company had made ''significant concessions,'' talks between the federal
government and the software giant broke down today and the judge trying to
mediate a settlement in the antitrust lawsuit said he was ending his effort.
Federal appeals court Judge Richard Posner said in a statement that the
disagreements are too deep-seated to be bridged. At issue is a lawsuit filed by
the federal government and 19 states alleging that Microsoft repeatedly engaged
in illegal anticompetitive behavior by using monopoly power. ''It's unfortunate
that a settlement wasn't possible,'' Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates said in a
conference call.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Americans Urged To Comply With Census
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today urged all Americans to participate
in this year's census, and took direct aim at Republicans who have grumbled
about the intrusiveness of some questions. ''Those who suggest that filling out
your census form isn't essential are plainly wrong,'' Clinton said in his weekly
radio address. His remarks coincided with Census Day, the April 1 once a decade
on which Americans are asked to tell the government who and where they are.
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush has said he's not sure he would
fill out the 53-question ''long form,'' which includes questions about income,
education, employment and health.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
First Lady, Gore Differ on Elian
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton today opposed Congressional
action to make Elian Gonzalez a resident of this country. The First Lady's
position puts her at odds with Vice President Al Gore. ''Hillary Clinton knows
that we must take politics out of this decision,'' said Clinton Senate campaign
spokesman Howard Wolfson. Clinton's position on Elian also put her at odds with
New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who maintains that the boy should be
granted U.S. citizenship.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Political Parties Hunt Campaign Cash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- While their likely presidential nominees advocate campaign
finance reform, the political parties are eagerly courting individuals,
corporations and unions willing to contribute $250,000 or more. The Republican
National Committee already reports 51 contributions of at least $250,000 in the
1999-2000 election season, twice as many as during the 1995-96 political
campaign. Figures for the Democrats are incomplete because of a different
reporting system, but their top donor category is the same.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report Outrages Aboriginal Groups
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Aboriginal groups are threatening to disrupt the
Olympic games over a report that the Australian government is playing down the
number of Aboriginal children forcibly placed with white families -- the
so-called ''stolen generation.'' New South Wales' 118 Aboriginal land councils
voted to march in protest on Sept. 16, the first full day of competition in the
games in Sydney, The Sun-Herald newspaper reported Sunday. Believing that
Aborigines were doomed and that absorbing the children was the only alternative,
the Australian government took an estimated 100,000 Aboriginal children from
their parents between 1910 and the 1970s.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
L.A. Janitors May Soon Strike
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Thousands of janitors in Los Angeles could vote to
exchange buckets and brooms for union banners this week, and union officials say
expiring contracts in other cities mean a work stoppage could expand. The
contract for the 8,500 janitors who empty trash and clean toilets at commercial
properties in downtown, Century City and elsewhere in Los Angeles County expired
Friday night. A strike vote planned for Monday will be followed by all-night
picketing, marches and chants, and civil disobedience, the union said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NY Cops Kill 2 Reputed Gang Members
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two undercover narcotics officers fatally shot two reputed
gang members after they robbed the policemen by brandishing fake handguns,
authorities said today. The shootings come with tensions in the city still high
after the fatal March 16 shooting of an unarmed black man. Police were quick to
defend the officers in this incident, which occurred during a Friday night drug
operation in Brooklyn. The dead suspects were identified as 19-year-old Tysheen
Bourne and 17-year-old Andre Fields, and were both black.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Michigan State Defeats Wisconsin 53-41
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Morris Peterson provided most of the offense as e
Michigan State moved within one victory of their first national title since 1979
with a bruising 53-41 triumph over Wisconsin tonight. The Spartans (31-7), who
have been focused on nothing but a national title since losing to Duke in the
national semifinals a year ago, failed to score a field goal for the final 11:42
of the first half.
</P>
