<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Rallies For Health Care Reform  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTIAN H. GEHRKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Banging drums and chanting ''HMOs got to
go,'' about 200 critics of managed health care rallied Saturday to
demand reform.
</P>
<P>
   A hearse led demonstrators down a Hollywood street while
doctors, nurses and patients carried signs with grim messages, such
as ''Widowed by HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We want a dialogue with Congress because managed care is
killing patients,'' said Dr. Ronald Bronow, a rally organizer.
''We'll keep on doing this, they'll keep on hearing from us. This
is the start of a patient revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of demonstrators did not come close to the 5,000
originally predicted for the rally, which was part of a nationwide
effort by the groups Physicians Who Care and the National Coalition
of Mental Health Professionals and Consumers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people promised they would come,'' said Dr. Charles D.
Goodman. ''But because the weather is so nice today, they didn't
show up.''
</P>
<P>
   In Northern California, about 50 people showed up for a San Jose
protest.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, Cincinnati Vice Mayor Minette Cooper presented a
proclamation offering civic support for the cause of health care
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Linda Peeno of Louisville, Ky., a former managed care
company doctor, said she quit her six-figure job in protest of the
current health care system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I denied thousands of patients care,'' Peeno said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Ted Strickland, D-Ohio, said a quality system of
health care delivery ought to be a right of every citizen in the
country.
</P>
</TEXT>
