<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lightning 3, Panthers 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. (AP) -- Scott Mellanby scored with 1:36 remaining
in regulation as the Florida Panthers rallied from two goals down
to tie Tampa Bay 3-3 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Florida outshot Tampa 12-1 in the third period after trailing
3-1 after two periods. Mellanby slid the puck past Zac Bierk off a
nice feed by Mark Parrish, who was inside the right circle.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Johnson scored a pair of goals and had an assist for Tampa
Bay in the physical contest. Vincent Lacavalier added a pair of
assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers, with Washington's 4-3 loss to Toronto, pulled
within four points of the Capitals for the Southeast Division
title.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning ended a nine-game losing streak in the series
dating to March 21, 1998. Tampa Bay had notched only one win in the
prior 14 meetings between the clubs. The Lightning haven't won a
road game from the Panthers since April 10, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning dropped to 0-7-9 in overtime. The Panthers are
2-21-2 when trailing after two periods.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay, coming off an impressive 6-3 victory over
playoff-bound Ottawa, jumped out to a 1-0 lead on Johnson's 18th
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Holzinger took the initial shot, which Mike Vernon
stopped, but Vernon didn't cover the puck and Johnson skated in and
poked it into the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers tied it at 1 just 2:38 into the second period on
Ray Whitney's 26th goal. Whitney scored after a shot by Robert
Svehla from the slot caromed off the back boards. Whitney reached a
new career high with 66 points.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Bure assisted on Whitney's goal, extending his scoring
streak to 11 games. It's his second such streak of the year,
becoming the only player in the NHL this season to accomplish the
feat. Bure, with two assist, is the first Panthers player to reach
90 points.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was marred by dirty play that included 62
minutes of penalties, 47 by Florida, and game misconducts issued to
Florida's Brad Ference and Mike Sillinger, who was traded from
Tampa March 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning wound up on a power play due to Ference's original
penalty, for slashing, and took advantage when Todd Warriner scored
to put Tampa up 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's second goal came at 14:24 of the second as he sent a
shot from the slot past Vernon, who had won his five prior starts.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Kvasha scored to make it 3-2 when he rebounded a miss by
Bure that went off Bierk's knees at 5:19 of the third. It was the
first point for Kvasha since Feb. 21 and his first goal since Jan.
21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
