<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volcano Evacuees Fear Worst Ahead  </HEADLINE>
By GINNY PARKER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- Thousands of townspeople hunkered down on the
hard wooden floors of makeshift emergency shelters for yet another
day Saturday as Mount Usu sputtered with more bursts of ash and
volcanic debris.
</P>
<P>
   Speedy orders to get everyone out of danger areas well before
Usu's first eruption won praise for the government. But after four
days in limbo, many evacuees feared the worst was still ahead --
more volcanic spitting and weeks, perhaps months, away from their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be hard to keep this up for the long term,'' said
Mutsuko Shimakura, 74, who came with her husband to a rescue center
for people with physical infirmities.
</P>
<P>
   The eruptions, which began Friday, dusted rice fields and other
crops with a blanket of fine, volcanic ash. Authorities have
reported no injuries or damage, but fears remained that that Usu
could spew a deadly mix of gas and rocks -- called a pyroclastic
flow -- that races down slopes and incinerates everything in its
path.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, plumes of white smoke continued to swell into the
sky, many coming from new craters that broke open in the latest
eruptions -- including one 100 yards from village homes.
</P>
<P>
   Experts warned that the changes made in the landscape by the
eruption, such as the craters, would cause long-term concerns for
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly there have been big changes in the topography where
the eruptions occurred,'' said Tadahide Ui, a volcano expert at
Hokkaido University. ''In those areas it will be impossible for
people's lives to go back to the way they originally were.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiromu Okada, also a professor at Hokkaido University, said of
particular concern was the formation of faults at the summit of the
mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very anxious about this evidence. Magma is pushing up
the center of this volcano,'' he said, adding there was still the
possibility of a major pyroclastic flow.
</P>
<P>
   More than 15,000 residents have been forced from their homes on
Hokkaido, Japan's northernmost main island, many leaving their dogs
tied up for what they expected would be only a short absence.
</P>
<P>
   Experts now say that looks increasingly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is our opinion that the main magma has yet to surface,''
volcanologist Hiromu Okada, also Hokkaido University, was quoted as
saying by Kyodo News.
</P>
<P>
   While authorities said their biggest problem at first was
providing necessities, they now face a trickier task: soothing
strained nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until yesterday, the main problems were getting food and
baths,'' said care worker Yoshikazu Kiyama. ''Now people are
feeling stress, so we have to provide psychological care. People
are really starting to want to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   At one rescue center in Date, at the volcano's base, men sat
chain-smoking, their faces flushed with alcohol. Other displaced
residents huddled in the next room, whispering in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuees groused at the slightest noise. About 240 people were
packed into one room.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last night, an old lady gave me the evil eye when I dropped my
flashlight and woke her up,'' said 15-year-old Masaharu Haru.
</P>
<P>
   Many were growing increasingly nervous about their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband is really stubborn and he didn't want to leave the
house,'' Shimakura said.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the slow and arduous recovery after Mount Usu's last
eruption, in 1978, it is easy to understand residents' fears.
</P>
<P>
   That time, the eruption was declared over nearly five years
after the volcano first burst. It left a huge dent in the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The region's tourism industry suffered $11.3 million in losses,
as well as $2 million in damage. The number of vacationers in the
scenic lake and hot spring resort area reportedly dropped 60
percent in the period. Overall damage, including lost income as
well as destroyed homes, totaled $503 million.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese central and local government officials were praised in
the press for their response to the emergency and credited with
preventing injuries and possibly saving lives.
</P>
<P>
   About 51,000 people live in the coastal city of Date and several
smaller towns near Usu, 475 miles north of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   At the initial signs of growing volcanic activity earlier this
week, officials in nearby villages and towns informed residents of
the imminent danger, urging them to evacuate as early as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials asked the Self-Defense Forces to help transport
the evacuees, and gave residents maps showing possible danger
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Those who remember Mount Usu's last eruption were pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ''This time, the reaction was completely different,'' said
Tsunaichi Watanabe, 74, a Date resident.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was so impressed to see the Self-Defense Forces coming into
the city in their trucks,'' he said, riding a bus back to town.
''When I saw that, I felt it's become a better world.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian Institution's Global Volcanism Program:
http://www.nmnh.si.edu/gvp/
</P>
<P>
   Volcanoes Online (geared toward children):
http://library.thinkquest.org/17457/english.html
</P>
<P>
   The Volcano Information Center:
http://www.geol.ucsb.edu/(tilde)fisher/
</P>
<P>
   The Electronic Volcano: http://www.dartmouth.edu/(tilde)volcano/
</P>
</TEXT>
