<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maine Reform Party Elects Delegates  </HEADLINE>
By FRANCIS X. QUINN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) -- The Reform Party of Maine's tiny state
convention on Saturday elected a five-member slate of national
delegates supporting presidential hopeful Patrick Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who has run previously for president as a Republican,
addressed the gathering prior to the voting, as did Natural Law
Party candidate John Hagelin.
</P>
<P>
   Outlining a platform emphasizing ''economic nationalism,''
Buchanan said the duty of the federal government in crafting trade
policy must be to ''stand up clearly for America first.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan by turns criticized the Clinton administration and the
Republican-led Congress for failing to effectively counter
production cutbacks by foreign oil producers and trade imbalances
with other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Denouncing incursions on U.S. sovereignty by organizations
ranging from the World Trade Organization to the United Nations,
Buchanan declared, ''no global institution is going to tell us
Americans how to govern ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, whose campaign brochures stress his opposition to
abortion, made no mention of that or other social issues during the
opening remarks of his 45-minute presentation to fewer than 100
listeners inside the auditorium of Cony High School.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin, a founder of the Natural Law Party and its presidential
nominee four years ago, offered himself as a candidate who could
represent a fusion coalition drawing on support from the Natural
Law, Reform and Green parties.
</P>
<P>
   With organizational energy that dominated the small gathering,
Buchanan backers prepared a slate of candidates supporting him and
mustered the votes to ensure victory for them.
</P>
<P>
   There were only about 30 voters and after the national delegates
were chosen, less ardent Buchanan supporters and uncommitted
candidates won election to other party posts.
</P>
<P>
   In Manchester, N.H., meanwhile, Buchanan supporters elected
themselves to head the state Reform Party on Saturday but others
claiming the Reform mantle in New Hampshire challenged the validity
of the session.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was not a Reform Party meeting,'' said John Talbott, the
previous acting party chairman who maintained he was not voted out
of office. ''That was a Buchanan for President meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott did not attend the Saturday session where about 80
Buchanan supporters met to elect new party officers. They claimed
Talbott and others had violated the party's by-laws by not holding
regular meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
