<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft-U.S. Gov't Talks Crumble
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Talks between the federal government and Microsoft broke down
today despite assertions by Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates that his company had
made ''significant concessions.'' Federal appeals court Judge Richard Posner
said he was ending his effort to mediate a settlement. Posner said in a
statement that the disagreements are too deep-seated to be bridged. At issue is
a lawsuit filed by the federal government and 19 states alleging that Microsoft
repeatedly engaged in illegal anticompetitive behavior by using monopoly power.
''It's unfortunate that a settlement wasn't possible,'' Gates said in a
conference call.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Volcano Evacuees Fear Worst Ahead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- Thousands of townspeople hunkered down on the hard wooden
floors of makeshift emergency shelters for yet another day today as Mount Usu
sputtered with more bursts of ash and volcanic debris. Speedy orders to get
everyone out of danger areas well before Usu's first eruption won praise for the
government. But after four days in limbo, many evacuees fear the worst was still
ahead -- more volcanic spitting and weeks, perhaps months, away from their
homes. More than 15,000 residents have been forced from their homes on Hokkaido,
Japan's northernmost main island.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protesters Oppose Returning Elian
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI, Fla. (AP) -- Even as U.S Attorney General Janet Reno appealed to
Americans not to further politicize the Elian Gonzalez case, about 100
Cuban-Americans protested the Immigration and Naturalization Service order today
to return 6-year-old boy to his father in Cuba. Reno, who favors returning Elian
to his family, spoke to students at the University of Virginia Law School on
Saturday and reiterated her position that the boy's father should have the right
to speak for him. The INS has threatened to revoke the boy's residency status,
but twice last week pushed back a deadline for the relatives to agree, now set
for 9 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Americans Urged To Comply With Census
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today urged all Americans to participate
in this year's census, and took direct aim at Republicans who have grumbled
about the intrusiveness of some questions. ''Those who suggest that filling out
your census form isn't essential are plainly wrong,'' Clinton said in his weekly
radio address. His remarks coincided with Census Day, the April 1 once a decade
on which Americans are asked to tell the government who and where they are.
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush has said he's not sure he would
fill out the 53-question ''long form,'' which includes questions about income,
education, employment and health.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Political Parties Hunt Campaign Cash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- While their likely presidential nominees advocate campaign
finance reform, the political parties are eagerly courting individuals,
corporations and unions willing to contribute $250,000 or more. The Republican
National Committee already reports 51 contributions of at least $250,000 in the
1999-2000 election season, twice as many as during the 1995-96 political
campaign. Figures for the Democrats are incomplete because of a different
reporting system, but their top donor category is the same.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
HSBC Bids $10.5B for French Bank
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The British banking group HSBC Holdings PLC announced Saturday
that it has made a $10.5 billion bid for Credit Commercial de France and that
the board of the French bank had unanimously recommended the offer to its
shareholders. The offer is for the purchase of all outstanding shares of the
French bank at a price of $144 per share in cash or, as an alternative, 13
shares of HSBC for each Credit Commercial share, valued at approximately $154
each. HSBC said the acquisition would give it a ''significant base for operation
in the Euro-zone,'' and bring relationships with most major French companies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Radio Host Art Bell Retiring
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Radio talk show host Art Bell announced today that he is
retiring for a second time -- and for good -- because of false allegations that
he is a child molester. Bell, whose ''Coast to Coast AM with Art Bell'' is
America's most popular overnight radio program, made the announcement to his
estimated 15 million listeners. Bell's program, heard on more than 400 stations
nationwide, deals with topics ranging from space aliens to FBI and CIA
conspiracies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Florida Defeats N.Carolina 71-59
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Florida, using the same 10-man rotation, full-court
press and balanced scoring that brought them to the Final Four, ended North
Carolina's improbable tournament run with a 71-59 victory tonight. Florida
(29-7) will meet Michigan State, which beat Wisconsin 53-41, in Monday night's
national championship game at the RCA Dome. Freshman Brett Nelson led the Gators
with 13 points, while Mike Miller and Udonis Haslem added 10 each.
</P>
