<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gene Elstun
</P>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. (AP) -- Gene Elstun, a teammate of Wilt
Chamberlain on the Kansas basketball team that lost in triple
overtime to North Carolina in the 1957 NCAA championship, died
Thursday of pancreatic cancer. He was 64.
</P>
<P>
   Elstun, also an accomplished golfer, was a manufacturer's
representative in the golf equipment industry.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Kansas City, Mo., and starred in basketball at
what was then Shawnee Mission Rural High School, now Shawnee
Mission North, captaining the team that won the 1953 state
championship.
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore at Kansas, the 6-foot-3 Elstun ranked second in
scoring with a 14.2 average. He averaged 12.8 points the following
season.
</P>
<P>
   As a senior in the 1956-57 season, with Chamberlain playing for
the Jayhawks for the first time, Elstun was co-captain of a team
that went 24-3 and made the NCAA Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks, champions of what was then the Big Seven
Conference, beat SMU and Oklahoma City in the regionals and
defeated San Francisco 80-56 in the championship semifinal. That
set up the championship game that North Carolina won 54-53.
</P>
<P>
Ed McCurdy
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Ed McCurdy, a leading 1950s folk music figure
whose songs were recorded by Johnny Cash, Arlo Guthrie and Joan
Baez, died March 23 in Halifax, Novia Scotia. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   McCurdy left his home in Willow Hill, Pa., for New York and a
singing career at age 18. After a failed bid at becoming a Frank
Sinatra-style nightclub singer, McCurdy turned to folk music during
the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, he headlined a series of shows at New York's Village
Vanguard and released his first album, ''Ed McCurdy Sings Songs of
the Canadian Maritimes.'' He later signed a deal with Elektra
Records, where he collaborated with another influential folk
singer, Ramblin' Jack Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, his songs were recorded by a variety of artists that
included Cash, Guthrie, Baez, Pete Seeger, and Simon and Garfunkel.
</P>
<P>
   After his music career waned, McCurdy moved to Nova Scotia in
1984 and became a character actor on Canadian television dramas.
</P>
<P>
Peter Pafiolis
</P>
<P>
   RICHFIELD, Minn. (AP) -- Peter Pafiolis, who served as the voice
for the Minnesota Education Association for 27 years and was known
for his passion for language, died Monday. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Pafiolis joined the Minnesota Education Association as public
relations director in 1962 and served the association until 1989.
Before joining the association, he was an education reporter for
the Saint Paul Pioneer Press and Dispatch for eight years and
worked in a different public relations job for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Pafiolis is survived by two daughters, one son and three
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
John Robert Starr
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- John Robert Starr, who helped change
the face of Arkansas journalism by leading an underdog newspaper to
victory in a bitter circulation war, died Saturday. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, a former Associated Press reporter and bureau chief, died
of an apparent heart attack in Del Norte, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was managing editor of the Arkansas Democrat as it battled
the Arkansas Gazette from 1978 to 1991. When the Democrat purchased
the Gazette's assets, Starr became managing editor of the
Democrat-Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   After 19 years with the AP, including 10 as the news service's
Little Rock bureau chief starting, Starr enrolled in graduate
school at the University of Tennessee in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, he was hired to lead the Democrat, then an afternoon
preparing for a head-to-head battle with the dominant Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were trying to go from being a second newspaper to being an
equivalent newspaper to the Gazette,'' Walter E. Hussman Jr.,
publisher of the Arkansas Democrat-Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   After the newspaper war, Starr remained as managing editor of
the Democrat-Gazette for less than a year -- but kept writing a
column seven days a week until the late 1990s, when he cut back to
three columns a week.
</P>
<P>
   He was often critical of Bill Clinton, both as president and
governor, but was genuinely touched when Clinton sent condolences
this year on the death of Starr's brother Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had a real soft side, but he never showed that to the
readers,'' Hussman said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House issued a statement Saturday night in which
Clinton conveyed his condolences to Starr's family and expressed
respect for Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was a sports writer at the Memphis Commercial Appeal
before joining the AP in Little Rock in 1957. He was promoted to AP
bureau chief in 1966 after serving for years as capitol reporter
and news editor.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Norma; two sons, John Starr and
Robert Starr, publisher of the Palatka (Fla.) Daily News; and a
daughter, Linda Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-01-00 2317 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
