<HEADLINE> Bonds Hits First Homer at New Park  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds didn't take long to become the
first player to homer at Pacific Bell Park, and his home-run ball
was rescued by a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds homered on the first pitch he saw from New York's Andy
Pettitte in the first inning of Saturday night's game between the
San Francisco Giants and the Yankees. It was the second preseason
game played at the new park -- no homers were hit Friday night as
the Giants played the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   The shot to right-center landed in what has been nicknamed
McCovey Cove, a body of water leading into San Francisco Bay. It
was named for Hall of Famer Willie McCovey.
</P>
</TEXT>
