<HEADLINE> Chicago Mayor Daley Hospitalized  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN LIPMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Mayor Richard M. Daley was hospitalized Saturday
after suffering chest pains.
</P>
<P>
   Daley was alert and in stable condition, but will be kept
overnight for observation at Northwestern Memorial Hospital,
doctors said. A battery of tests came up negative for heart
problems, Dr. Steven DeAngeles said.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's family physician, Dr. Ed Newman, said Daley was
complaining of vague chest discomfort and his blood pressure was
elevated when he was taken to the hospital. His blood pressure had
returned to normal Saturday night, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was taken to the hospital from his home at about 3:30
p.m. by paramedics as a precautionary measure on Newman's advice.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had vague discomfort so I thought the advisable thing to do
was to hospitalize him to make sure the mayor was safe and sound,''
Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, 57, had attended a neighborhood policing meeting earlier
Saturday and was resting when the pain began, spokeswoman Jackie
Heard said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said he wasn't feeling well earlier in the day,'' Heard
said, ''but then he went on to give a speech to 3,000 people at his
usual pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Rod Sierra said Daley is in good shape and works out
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ''He works out regularly and is in very good shape,'' Sierra
said.
</P>
<P>
   Daley is the son of Chicago's legendary Boss, Mayor Richard J.
Daley, who died of a heart attack in 1976. The younger Daley easily
extended his family's political dynasty last year when he defeated
Rep. Bobby Rush to win a third full term.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's first black mayor, Harold Washington, died of a heart
attack in office in 1987.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
